00:00:20.791 --> 00:00:22.940
PROFESSOR: So tonight,
the first part of tonight

00:00:22.940 --> 00:00:26.450
is the financing sources panel.

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:28.340
And we have two of our
three members here.

00:00:28.340 --> 00:00:30.512
So I'll invite
them to take seats.

00:00:30.512 --> 00:00:32.220
Julianne, we're putting
you in the middle

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:37.685
because you have to keep the
guys on the end, and Axel.

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:43.040
And what I'm going to
do is, to give them

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:47.310
some context about where we are
in the course, just do a recap,

00:00:47.310 --> 00:00:47.950
so they know.

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:51.080
And then I'll have them
introduce themselves

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:52.470
and we'll go from there.

00:00:52.470 --> 00:00:56.160
It'll be a Q&amp;A after a brief
description of what they do.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:58.400
So where's the class so far?

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:01.930
We started off two nights
ago with an introduction

00:01:01.930 --> 00:01:05.170
to business plans and planning.

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:09.000
We talked about the importance--
the basic tasks were

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.220
to figure out how
to create value

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:15.460
and how to capture value,
both for the entrepreneur

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:16.750
and for investors.

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:18.270
There are the three whys.

00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:18.840
Why this?

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:20.775
Why is this an important
thing that you're

00:01:20.775 --> 00:01:22.650
doing that you're going
to spend your time on

00:01:22.650 --> 00:01:24.745
or you want people to
invest resources in.

00:01:24.745 --> 00:01:26.210
Why now?

00:01:26.210 --> 00:01:28.360
Why now is the
right time to do it.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:31.820
We've all been on the burning
leading edge of the wrong time.

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:32.815
And then why this team?

00:01:32.815 --> 00:01:35.356
The investors are going to say,
well, is this the right team?

00:01:35.356 --> 00:01:39.777
And you need to be asking, do I
have the right team of people?

00:01:39.777 --> 00:01:41.610
And then if you get
those first three right,

00:01:41.610 --> 00:01:44.220
you should be asking
yourself the fourth why,

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:46.960
which is why won't this work?

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:49.170
What am I missing here?

00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:52.140
That was the first
part of Tuesday night.

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:54.170
And then Steve Purse
came in and talked

00:01:54.170 --> 00:01:56.497
about how to give
a pitch-- taking

00:01:56.497 --> 00:01:58.580
all of that planning you're
going to do and put it

00:01:58.580 --> 00:02:00.980
in a way to communicate.

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:03.230
He focused pretty much
on pitching to investors,

00:02:03.230 --> 00:02:06.110
but he did point out
the same concepts

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:10.900
apply to pitching to
partnerships and other things.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:13.220
Last night we had Bob
Jones come in and talked

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:16.490
about finding your customer.

00:02:16.490 --> 00:02:17.185
It's not sales.

00:02:17.185 --> 00:02:18.110
It's not marketing.

00:02:18.110 --> 00:02:21.030
It's finding your customer.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:22.460
What do they want?

00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:24.380
What will they pay for it?

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:25.790
How do you find them?

00:02:25.790 --> 00:02:30.590
And he gave some really
personal examples of situations

00:02:30.590 --> 00:02:35.110
where he succeeded and
where he did not succeed.

00:02:35.110 --> 00:02:36.900
And it was very interesting.

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:39.290
I got him to speak after
the break about something

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:40.810
he's actually working on.

00:02:40.810 --> 00:02:43.540
So that's an important part
of what this class has been.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:45.914
It's not about abstract
thinking about things.

00:02:45.914 --> 00:02:47.580
The people that are
talking are actually

00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:49.570
doing the things
they talk about.

00:02:49.570 --> 00:02:52.250
And he's right in
the middle of that.

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:54.520
And then we had
Rich Kibble come in

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:56.717
and talk about business models.

00:02:56.717 --> 00:02:57.675
So I've got a customer.

00:02:57.675 --> 00:02:59.240
I think I have a
value, but what's

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.770
the model that I'm going
to use to generate revenue.

00:03:02.770 --> 00:03:04.616
The second part of
tonight, Charlie Tillett,

00:03:04.616 --> 00:03:05.990
who will come in
after the break,

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:08.230
is going to do
financial projections.

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:09.900
How do I take all
of that, figure

00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:12.050
out what it means economically?

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:14.550
And we talked about it
being not a static process

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:20.627
but a dynamic process-- test,
redo, until you get it right.

00:03:20.627 --> 00:03:22.210
So once you've done
all that planning,

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:24.350
you're going to
need some resources.

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:26.560
And one of the
resources is funding.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:29.480
So that's what
the panel is about

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:31.330
The people on the
panel represent

00:03:31.330 --> 00:03:34.320
sort of organized
forms of financing.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:37.670
But entrepreneurs get
financed in a variety of ways.

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:40.170
So a lot of people talk
about just venture capital.

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:41.860
But plenty of great
companies have

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:47.140
been launched through angel,
friends and family type money.

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:50.590
A traditional way
is using customers.

00:03:50.590 --> 00:03:51.860
You work for a customer.

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:54.680
You see what they don't want.

00:03:54.680 --> 00:03:57.210
You then try to move
from a services business

00:03:57.210 --> 00:04:00.060
into a product
business, productize it.

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:01.530
There are grants.

00:04:01.530 --> 00:04:05.640
National Science Foundation,
small business innovation

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:08.770
research funding, SBIR.

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:10.320
This money is
available from each

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:14.663
of 11 or so federal agencies and
can be up to a million dollars.

00:04:14.663 --> 00:04:16.079
I'm working with
a company I think

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:20.300
is at a million dollars
of SBIR funding.

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:26.120
And we have more recent types of
funding, which crowd sourcing,

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:28.080
where the following at
Kickstarter and others

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:30.870
have been to fund products.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:32.990
And we're just beginning
under the JOBS Act that

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:36.180
was passed a year or
so ago to have rules

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:38.580
out that are going to get
finalized around crowd

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:40.690
sourcing of investment.

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:42.650
So in Kickstarter,
traditionally it's

00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:44.540
I want to find this product.

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:46.110
In the crowd funding
of investment,

00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:50.740
it'll be I want to put money
into a company or a business.

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:53.040
And they're probably
some other ways

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:56.370
people have funded,
like credit cards.

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:59.990
Business plan competitions
have launched companies.

00:04:59.990 --> 00:05:02.180
I was involved in
the company who

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:06.470
got launched because they got
sued for trademark infringement

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:10.050
and settled and sold the
name to another company

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:11.137
and got $25,000 for that.

00:05:11.137 --> 00:05:12.470
So that's how they got launched.

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:14.290
So lots of different
ways entrepreneurs

00:05:14.290 --> 00:05:16.950
got to be creative.

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:19.830
But for the panel, we'll
start with the basic organize

00:05:19.830 --> 00:05:21.470
and maybe we'll
open it up to Q&amp;A.

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:23.677
So I've asked each
of the panel members

00:05:23.677 --> 00:05:25.260
to introduce
themselves-- a little bit

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:28.860
about their background, what
you should know about them.

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:31.430
They're entrepreneurs in the
sense that they raise money

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:33.690
from people in
order to turn around

00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.120
and invest it in your project.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:38.669
So just as you're an
entrepreneur to them,

00:05:38.669 --> 00:05:40.460
they're an entrepreneur
to their investors.

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:43.150
And asked them to talk two,
three, four minutes-- whatever

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:45.860
you feel comfortable--
to set the stage.

00:05:45.860 --> 00:05:47.809
So Axel, we'll start with you.

00:05:47.809 --> 00:05:48.600
AXEL BICHARA: Sure.

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:50.110
Happy to start.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:52.230
Good evening, everybody.

00:05:52.230 --> 00:05:55.220
I'll go through my background
a little bit first.

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:57.180
I am from Germany originally.

00:05:57.180 --> 00:06:01.610
Came to MIT in the late '80s,
studied mechanical engineering,

00:06:01.610 --> 00:06:05.440
and sat in one of these
classes and ended up

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:08.600
co-founding a software company,
mechanical design automation

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:13.840
software company, out of--
at the time it was 15-375.

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:18.690
And we raised venture money
relatively quickly $1.5 million

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:20.720
to start with and then
some follow on rounds.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.070
I was VP engineering
in that company.

00:06:23.070 --> 00:06:26.200
We sold it after about
four or five years.

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:28.420
I then became a
venture capitalist,

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:32.020
was at Atlas Venture
for 19 years in total.

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:35.470
Raised and invested about
$2 billion to $2.5 billion

00:06:35.470 --> 00:06:38.350
while I was there and
did mostly early stage,

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:43.220
self slash early stage
technology startups.

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:47.900
I left there about two years
ago to do deals on my own.

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:51.410
And so I have helped start
a couple of companies

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:54.480
and have made a number of
personal investments as well.

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:58.250
And one of the
companies I helped start

00:06:58.250 --> 00:07:01.030
is actually an accelerator
for hardware startups.

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:03.190
Called Bolt in downtown Boston.

00:07:03.190 --> 00:07:09.292
So that's another financing
model I got exposed to

00:07:09.292 --> 00:07:12.470
and really got involved with
where you don't provide just

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:15.980
capital and some high level
expertise and strategy,

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:22.180
but real hands-on
work on product,

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:24.830
much more hands-on company
building, team building,

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:26.930
than you do in a
venture capital.

00:07:26.930 --> 00:07:30.550
And we're doing that with very
early stage companies there.

00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:33.710
So I can I think in
the evening here talk

00:07:33.710 --> 00:07:35.150
about it angel financing.

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:36.560
I'm an angel.

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:38.950
I'm involved in
this accelerator.

00:07:38.950 --> 00:07:41.990
I've been in the VC
business for a long time.

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:46.500
And I'm also involved
in a company called

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:50.020
Dragon Innovation,
which is a crowdfunding

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:51.850
company for hardware startups.

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:54.590
So I think that's actually one
of the very interesting ways

00:07:54.590 --> 00:07:58.050
of getting companies off
the ground that may not

00:07:58.050 --> 00:08:00.852
show necessary the highest
potential from the beginning,

00:08:00.852 --> 00:08:02.560
but to launch an
initial product and then

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:06.440
kind of see what happens.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:12.060
So in all this experience
I've accumulated,

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:14.027
probably maybe the
most important lesson--

00:08:14.027 --> 00:08:15.860
the most important
lesson is probably always

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:17.570
work with good people.

00:08:17.570 --> 00:08:20.530
Whoever your investors are,
you can't fire your investors.

00:08:20.530 --> 00:08:25.870
You need to select carefully
who you end up working with.

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:29.010
But also a match between
the financing source

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:32.480
and where you are as
a company in terms

00:08:32.480 --> 00:08:35.789
of the potential of the market,
the potential of the team

00:08:35.789 --> 00:08:37.039
and everything.

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:41.280
And often people think,
you're only a great company

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:43.289
if you raise VC eventually.

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:44.720
That's just so not true.

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:47.870
That's probably 1 in a
100 interesting startups

00:08:47.870 --> 00:08:50.750
is really suitable for
VC at the beginning.

00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:55.200
And it depends a
little on the stage,

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:58.000
a little bit on the potential,
and also the potential

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.630
may only discover over time.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:05.616
So I think that's the
great and also-- great

00:09:05.616 --> 00:09:07.490
other ways of getting
company off the ground.

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:10.420
And one of the things every
good entrepreneur is focused on

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:11.070
is dilutions.

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:14.232
So you want to be
kept really-- you

00:09:14.232 --> 00:09:16.190
want to be capital
efficient, but also dilution

00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:18.860
efficient from the beginning.

00:09:18.860 --> 00:09:21.520
And I think that often
means-- mean crowdfunding is

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:24.610
a great way to get pretty
much non-dilutive capital

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:25.220
for a product.

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:30.690
But whether it's friends
and family money,

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:35.190
incubators, accelerators,
angels-- and then of course VCs

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:37.330
have been going to
very early stage

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:40.350
funding as well, where you
have a number of VCs writing

00:09:40.350 --> 00:09:45.090
$100,000 to let's say a
$500,000 checks with very, very

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:48.210
low barrier to getting a deal
done, which can be attractive.

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:51.210
But it's attractive
in terms of you

00:09:51.210 --> 00:09:54.140
get capital relatively
easily and quickly.

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:57.150
But the question then
is, is that actually

00:09:57.150 --> 00:10:00.660
the right VC to help you build
the company in the long term.

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:05.150
Is VC the right sort
of financing to build

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:06.880
that company long term?

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:10.190
So I guess we can
zoom in to all of that

00:10:10.190 --> 00:10:12.020
as the evening progresses.

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:14.082
And I guess I'll stop here
with the introduction.

00:10:14.082 --> 00:10:14.790
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:10:14.790 --> 00:10:17.710
Well, before I ask
Julianne to speak,

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:20.735
Axel has been here before
to talk about this.

00:10:20.735 --> 00:10:23.540
And as I was putting together
the panel thinking, who's

00:10:23.540 --> 00:10:25.870
the right mix of
people, it struck me

00:10:25.870 --> 00:10:29.980
that your recent venture Bolt
fit well with nuts and bolts.

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:30.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:30.520 --> 00:10:33.320
But I did ask you
to figure out who

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:35.000
I could get for the nut part.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.586
So we haven't figured
that one out yet.

00:10:37.586 --> 00:10:40.150
Welcome.

00:10:40.150 --> 00:10:42.200
Julianne, you're not
the nut by any means.

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:44.420
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: Well,
I guess we'll leave that up

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:46.960
to the audience to decide.

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:53.007
So before launching into
my background and my focus

00:10:53.007 --> 00:10:55.090
and my reason for being
here on the panel tonight,

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:59.400
let me just say that the
thing that I hope all of you

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:03.525
recognize by the end of tonight,
if you don't already know it,

00:11:03.525 --> 00:11:09.240
is that every form of
capital has a use and a cost.

00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:13.050
And different forms of
capital are appropriate

00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:15.350
not only at different
stages, as Axel said,

00:11:15.350 --> 00:11:17.570
but for different
kinds of businesses.

00:11:17.570 --> 00:11:19.740
So you've already
been challenged

00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:21.090
in your first session in

00:11:21.090 --> 00:11:24.220
And to a lesser extent
again, in second session,

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:27.380
to think about why
you're doing this

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:30.940
and what you ultimately
aim to accomplish.

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:33.590
The answer to that question
is really important

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:35.180
for a variety of
reasons, not least

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:37.870
of which is to guide
you in making decisions

00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:41.070
about the appropriate
resources to call upon

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:43.160
to achieve that goal.

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:45.070
And one of those being capital.

00:11:45.070 --> 00:11:48.930
And there are very, very
different kinds of capital

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:51.270
that have different
uses, different benefits,

00:11:51.270 --> 00:11:53.090
and different costs.

00:11:53.090 --> 00:11:55.680
And by the way, I can't
remember the number, Joe.

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:56.460
You might know it.

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:58.485
But it's a minority
fraction of companies

00:11:58.485 --> 00:12:02.050
that they go to IPO that
were ever venture funded.

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:04.770
It's something less
than a quarter.

00:12:04.770 --> 00:12:07.650
It's like 16% or 17% percent.

00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:09.950
Do you remember, Axel.

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:13.340
AXEL BICHARA: I bet it's
less than that, actually.

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:18.510
And so many of the
great wealth creation

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:21.870
stories I found who never
have raised money, or just

00:12:21.870 --> 00:12:24.370
raised tiny amounts of money
and kept it all for themselves.

00:12:24.370 --> 00:12:26.547
If you can pull it
off, it's a great way--

00:12:26.547 --> 00:12:28.880
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: So there
are lots of preconceptions,

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:31.820
as Axel mentioned about, it's
only a really good company

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:34.440
if it's venture backed
or you only really

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:38.790
have steep growth potential, if
you can attract venture money.

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:40.950
I really hope that by
the end of this evening,

