00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:51.690
I came here in the mid '80s.

00:12:51.690 --> 00:12:56.180
I double majored in aerospace
engineering and literature,

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:58.440
neither of which
would lead anybody

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:02.880
to imagine that I'd be on
this panel here tonight.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:06.215
And my first career was in the
manned space flight business.

00:13:06.215 --> 00:13:08.640
It was a great first career.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:10.770
When I came to the end
of that first career,

00:13:10.770 --> 00:13:14.000
I was looking for
something that was equally

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.050
challenging and very different.

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:19.620
And I ended up co-founding
a company called

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:21.700
Greenfuel Technologies
before there

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:24.149
was such a thing as clean tech.

00:13:24.149 --> 00:13:25.940
As a matter of fact,
at that point in time,

00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:29.110
the greens and browns feared and
loathed each other, absolutely

00:13:29.110 --> 00:13:32.040
wanted nothing to
do with one another.

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:33.730
And here we were
founding a company

00:13:33.730 --> 00:13:36.220
that was algae biofuels.

00:13:36.220 --> 00:13:42.130
And I'm very proud of the fact
that in the time that company

00:13:42.130 --> 00:13:45.360
was alive, we actually
managed to change

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:48.970
the tenor of those exchanges.

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:51.740
In fact, we ended up
being frequently featured

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:56.230
in industry magazines like
Industrial Light and Power,

00:13:56.230 --> 00:13:58.930
which is about as far as
you can get from Mother

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:02.600
Jones in the known universe.

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:07.380
So I've been on the entrepreneur
side of the table, too.

00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:09.900
One of the things that
is important to notice

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:17.230
about that is we raised about
$23 million in-- good evening.

00:14:17.230 --> 00:14:24.570
We raised about $23 million, had
a very interesting proposition,

00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:28.930
made some mistakes, encountered
significant obstacles,

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:30.460
had a good team.

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:35.820
And when the market cratered
and project finance went away,

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:38.320
we defaulted on all
their contracts.

00:14:38.320 --> 00:14:40.520
And that was the
end of the company.

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:45.870
So there are many
things that can trip you

00:14:45.870 --> 00:14:51.720
up that have nothing to do with
the things that you thought of

00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:54.280
or the things that
you planned on.

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:57.290
Interestingly enough in
the entrepreneurial realm,

00:14:57.290 --> 00:14:59.890
having a company crater
is not necessarily

00:14:59.890 --> 00:15:03.660
the death knell of your
career as an entrepreneur.

00:15:03.660 --> 00:15:07.390
I went on to be involved in
a handful of other companies.

00:15:07.390 --> 00:15:09.460
By then, there was such
thing as clean tech.

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:12.200
And having been
involved before there

00:15:12.200 --> 00:15:19.280
was even a commonly understood
wave or trend or segment,

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:30.403
I was-- a venture mentoring
service, clean tech open,

00:15:30.403 --> 00:15:39.180
the 100K-- mentoring and judging
a bunch of really interesting

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:43.250
startups, some of which never
actually went on to launch.

00:15:43.250 --> 00:15:45.330
Many, in fact, didn't.

00:15:45.330 --> 00:15:49.610
But the teams would join
and break part and reform.

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:51.560
And that's probably
something that you also

00:15:51.560 --> 00:15:55.530
talk about in terms of the way
that you form teams together.

00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:59.390
As Axel mentioned, really
above all, the most important

00:15:59.390 --> 00:16:03.305
decision you make
every day is who

00:16:03.305 --> 00:16:05.945
to work with-- who to work
with on your team, who

00:16:05.945 --> 00:16:11.630
to work with as investors,
who to work with as partners,

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:14.030
who to work with as vendors.

00:16:14.030 --> 00:16:17.736
Ultimately that is far and away
the most important decision

00:16:17.736 --> 00:16:19.360
you make.

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:22.410
So having done all this
mentoring and judging

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:26.380
and blah blah blah, of
course I found myself

00:16:26.380 --> 00:16:29.550
drifting perilously
close to pretending I

00:16:29.550 --> 00:16:31.210
knew something useful.

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:35.670
And a friend and
colleague and I had

00:16:35.670 --> 00:16:38.530
been discussing
for about two years

00:16:38.530 --> 00:16:41.545
some trends we saw going
on-- not exclusively

00:16:41.545 --> 00:16:44.234
here in the Boston area,
but especially here

00:16:44.234 --> 00:16:45.970
in the entrepreneurial
community.

00:16:45.970 --> 00:16:48.870
And it's slowly
dawned on us that we

00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:52.120
had what sounded an awful lot
like an investment thesis.

00:16:52.120 --> 00:16:55.250
So in a very
entrepreneurial way,

00:16:55.250 --> 00:17:02.840
we wrote that down, started
showing it to people.

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:05.947
Keeping things secret is
not a great way to start.

00:17:05.947 --> 00:17:07.280
We started showing it to people.

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:08.849
We showed it to
everybody we thought

00:17:08.849 --> 00:17:11.220
would be able to
give us a candid

00:17:11.220 --> 00:17:14.940
response to the question,
is this completely wrong?

00:17:14.940 --> 00:17:17.300
What have we gotten wrong
and what have we missed?

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:18.780
What have we imagined?

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:21.170
What have we left out?

00:17:21.170 --> 00:17:23.680
Why will this not work?

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:27.869
And we did that for
about five months.

00:17:27.869 --> 00:17:30.920
And we got some great
feedback and we ended up

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:34.190
founding and new seed
stage venture firm

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:37.250
here in Boston area
called Vodia Ventures.

00:17:37.250 --> 00:17:42.290
That firm is now a year
old and we are still

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:45.980
raising our first
fund, so we are also,

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:51.540
as Joe alluded, we also raise
capital for our investors.

00:17:51.540 --> 00:17:54.140
And we've done
four deals so far.

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:56.630
So we've made four
investments in companies

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:58.220
here in the Boston area.

00:17:58.220 --> 00:18:01.030
And we don't focus on
clean tech, per se.

00:18:01.030 --> 00:18:03.680
We invest in segments
that people often

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:06.570
associate with
clean tech-- energy,

00:18:06.570 --> 00:18:09.290
air, water, food
security, public health,

00:18:09.290 --> 00:18:12.654
are the two that kind of
don't fit the clean tech set.

00:18:12.654 --> 00:18:14.320
And I'd be happy to
talk with any of you

00:18:14.320 --> 00:18:16.770
afterwards about why
those sectors are--

00:18:16.770 --> 00:18:19.220
why are we doing that.

00:18:19.220 --> 00:18:21.150
But the thing that
I'd really like

00:18:21.150 --> 00:18:25.120
to finish up this sort of
background monologue on

00:18:25.120 --> 00:18:28.860
is, when you are
thinking that you

00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:36.570
might want to go to an outside
investor to fund your company,

00:18:36.570 --> 00:18:39.660
as Joe alluded and as
Axel did as well, it's

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:43.725
really important not only
to know what kind of money

00:18:43.725 --> 00:18:47.630
you want and how much and
how much dilution you're

00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:50.640
willing to accept and what
an appropriate model is

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:55.560
for your stage and all the
rest, but are your interests

00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:58.790
and investor's interests
actually aligned?

00:18:58.790 --> 00:19:01.220
Do you share the same interests?

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:06.010
You're going to be working with
this person, an actual person,

00:19:06.010 --> 00:19:11.610
very intimately for an
extended period of time.

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:16.260
And so you really do want
to be very, very careful.

00:19:16.260 --> 00:19:19.520
You don't want to
send your elevator

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:22.420
pitch or your
presentation to everybody

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:24.440
you think might
possibly be interested.

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:26.390
You really want to
be very selective, as

00:19:26.390 --> 00:19:28.700
selective as you are
about your team members,

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:32.760
in picking the people
you think you probably

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:35.690
are going to share a good
working relationship with.

