So we're not just
working with companies

00:26:50.680 --> 00:26:54.950
that are-- three guys out
of MIT and the slide deck.

00:26:54.950 --> 00:26:56.249
Some offers are long.

00:26:56.249 --> 00:26:57.790
Some have been
software entrepreneurs

00:26:57.790 --> 00:27:01.560
before, are looking for
the expertise to getting

00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:03.960
a piece of hardware to market.

00:27:03.960 --> 00:27:05.950
So if the company has,
for instance, raised

00:27:05.950 --> 00:27:08.680
a bunch of venture capital,
sort of the totally formulaic

00:27:08.680 --> 00:27:11.190
approach of a Y
Combinator wouldn't work.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:14.644
So we have the formula
and then the rule,

00:27:14.644 --> 00:27:16.560
and then the exception
to the rule, basically.

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:19.110
And my philosophy
and our philosophy

00:27:19.110 --> 00:27:22.580
is, if there's a good company
and a good entrepreneur

00:27:22.580 --> 00:27:25.330
that we want to
work with, there's

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:27.714
a way to get a deal done that
makes sense for everybody.

00:27:27.714 --> 00:27:30.130
PROFESSOR: Are you willing to
tell us the default formula?

00:27:30.130 --> 00:27:30.921
AXEL BICHARA: Yeah.

00:27:30.921 --> 00:27:35.320
The default formula is, we
take 10% of common stock.

00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:38.180
We put in 50K.

00:27:38.180 --> 00:27:42.100
But the main thing you get
is you work with us for six

00:27:42.100 --> 00:27:45.470
to nine months basically
around the clock helping

00:27:45.470 --> 00:27:48.360
build product,
helping build team,

00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:50.880
get the company set
up for financing.

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:53.980
And there's often
the discussion, well,

00:27:53.980 --> 00:27:56.450
it's only 50K.

00:27:56.450 --> 00:27:57.320
What's evaluation?

00:27:57.320 --> 00:27:58.320
You kind of do the math.

00:27:58.320 --> 00:28:02.060
And the answer I normally
give is, let's take the 50K.

00:28:02.060 --> 00:28:03.444
Give it to a charity.

00:28:03.444 --> 00:28:05.860
The reason for coming here is
everything else we're doing.

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:07.200
It's not the 50K.

00:28:07.200 --> 00:28:12.710
So it's very much
a company building

00:28:12.710 --> 00:28:16.440
is a value we provide in
this particular case, which

00:28:16.440 --> 00:28:18.250
is really diametrically
opposed from what

00:28:18.250 --> 00:28:21.330
I did in the past, which was
big VC firm where it's really

00:28:21.330 --> 00:28:23.190
all about the capital.

00:28:23.190 --> 00:28:27.770
But that goes back to
what stage are you at

00:28:27.770 --> 00:28:29.170
and what do you need help with?

00:28:29.170 --> 00:28:31.460
And maybe one more comment
on the hardware thing--

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:36.520
in the amount of money
and time companies

00:28:36.520 --> 00:28:40.480
I invested at Atlas that was
wasted because we made kind

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:42.230
of beginner's mistakes
in getting hardware

00:28:42.230 --> 00:28:45.920
products to market
would have been

00:28:45.920 --> 00:28:48.645
significant value added if
something like Bolt had exited,

00:28:48.645 --> 00:28:50.925
even for a VC
company at the time.

00:28:50.925 --> 00:28:54.030
AMIR NASHAT: Can I make one
comment about incubators?

00:28:54.030 --> 00:28:57.710
And as Axel put, now come in
different shapes and sizes.

00:28:57.710 --> 00:29:00.640
One thing I noticed as a
voyeur at Dogpatch Labs.

00:29:00.640 --> 00:29:03.540
We had set up Dogpatch
Labs some years ago.

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:06.570
It's now exists within
Cambridge Innovation Center.

00:29:06.570 --> 00:29:10.666
It's more the value of being
around other people when

00:29:10.666 --> 00:29:12.290
you're trying to
evaluate these places.

00:29:12.290 --> 00:29:13.730
One is the services
they provide.

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:16.270
The other is actually
the value of being

00:29:16.270 --> 00:29:19.370
around sitting next to someone
who's doing better than you,

00:29:19.370 --> 00:29:21.940
and how that motivates
you, and there's

00:29:21.940 --> 00:29:24.190
this competitive
dynamic that kicks in.

00:29:24.190 --> 00:29:25.540
And you could watch it actually.

00:29:25.540 --> 00:29:27.760
Whenever I would
over there, someone

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:29.790
would get off the
phone with Pepsi

00:29:29.790 --> 00:29:32.100
and they were talking to
some VD person over there.

00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:34.290
And you could see the other
teams around them really kind

00:29:34.290 --> 00:29:35.456
of-- what have I done today?

00:29:35.456 --> 00:29:38.377
Maybe I'm a biotech or maybe I'm
a software company or something

00:29:38.377 --> 00:29:39.960
and I've got nothing
to do with Pepsi.

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:42.084
But it just gets you
thinking, what did I do today?

00:29:42.084 --> 00:29:44.600
And you could feel
the energy that grew.

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:47.580
So I think surrounding yourself
in an environment where

00:29:47.580 --> 00:29:49.240
it feels like people
are quite intense

00:29:49.240 --> 00:29:51.190
is actually
surprisingly valuable.

00:29:51.190 --> 00:29:54.150
And I think for a lot
of people that benefit

00:29:54.150 --> 00:29:55.660
from going into
these environments,

00:29:55.660 --> 00:29:57.830
whether it's an incubator
or accelerator or anything

00:29:57.830 --> 00:30:00.920
else-- sitting at home alone
and having to motivate yourself

00:30:00.920 --> 00:30:02.830
is actually quite
difficult a lot.

00:30:02.830 --> 00:30:04.000
It's like going to the gym.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.001
Some days you're great
and some days you're not.

00:30:06.001 --> 00:30:07.750
It just kind of helps
if you're at the gym

00:30:07.750 --> 00:30:09.200
with a bunch of
other people that

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:11.420
are kind of running
around acting like they're

00:30:11.420 --> 00:30:12.710
lifting a lot of weight.

00:30:12.710 --> 00:30:14.461
So I just think
that's one part I

00:30:14.461 --> 00:30:15.710
would look at when I evaluate.

00:30:15.710 --> 00:30:16.900
It is a soft factors.

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:18.390
It's obviously
not a hard factor.

00:30:21.856 --> 00:30:23.522
PROFESSOR: We have
some other questions?

00:30:23.522 --> 00:30:24.438
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:33.570 --> 00:30:35.820
PROFESSOR: Yeah, we haven't
covered that in the class,

00:30:35.820 --> 00:30:37.320
so if you want to
just take a moment

00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:39.216
and explain it to the
people that don't know.

00:30:39.216 --> 00:30:40.340
AXEL BICHARA: Oh, explain?

00:30:40.340 --> 00:30:41.940
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: Sure.

00:30:41.940 --> 00:30:42.440
Go ahead.

00:30:42.440 --> 00:30:44.770
AXEL BICHARA: So explain
convertible note?

00:30:44.770 --> 00:30:51.345
So an equity deal is
not a convertible note.

00:30:51.345 --> 00:30:52.220
I'll start with that.

00:30:52.220 --> 00:30:55.190
Equity deal is you basically
sell shares in your company.

00:30:55.190 --> 00:30:58.700
You give away a percentage for
the capital that gets invested.

00:30:58.700 --> 00:31:03.270
Convertible note is basically
you basically borrow money

00:31:03.270 --> 00:31:06.610
and you owe that money
back to the investors

00:31:06.610 --> 00:31:09.650
unless there's an event
under which the note converts

00:31:09.650 --> 00:31:10.900
into equity.

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:13.607
So may or may not
convert into equity

00:31:13.607 --> 00:31:15.440
depending on what the
terms of the note are.

00:31:15.440 --> 00:31:18.380
Often somebody
does, as an example,

00:31:18.380 --> 00:31:22.420
let's say, $500,000
convertible note

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:25.310
that has a term that says it
converts into the next equity

00:31:25.310 --> 00:31:29.070
round of financing off a
million dollars or more.

00:31:29.070 --> 00:31:32.830
And so if there's such
an equity financing,

00:31:32.830 --> 00:31:34.690
it converts and there's
some other terms

00:31:34.690 --> 00:31:37.030
like a discount interest rate.

00:31:37.030 --> 00:31:39.420
Or it may not convert
if the company,

00:31:39.420 --> 00:31:41.880
for instance-- well, if it goes
bankrupt, the money's gone.

00:31:41.880 --> 00:31:44.180
If the company is
acquired, there's

00:31:44.180 --> 00:31:49.270
typically a term where you get
1 and 1/2 to 3 times your money

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:52.030
back of the note.

00:31:52.030 --> 00:31:54.855
So that's kind of the basics.

00:31:58.460 --> 00:32:01.270
So why did convertible
notes become so popular?

00:32:01.270 --> 00:32:03.470
It's very easy and
quick to get done.

00:32:03.470 --> 00:32:06.050
It's a one to two page document.

00:32:06.050 --> 00:32:08.480
And as an entrepreneur,
you get the money quickly

00:32:08.480 --> 00:32:13.530
and there's no more
complicated legal documents

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:15.710
to do an actual equity deal.

00:32:15.710 --> 00:32:18.380
On the flip side is,
you owe the money.

00:32:18.380 --> 00:32:20.570
It's debt until it converts.

00:32:20.570 --> 00:32:25.220
And normally the rule with
debt is that if things go well,

00:32:25.220 --> 00:32:26.930
it's a good thing to have taken.

00:32:26.930 --> 00:32:30.510
If things don't go so well,
you may end up regretting it.

00:32:30.510 --> 00:32:32.450
Now in many startups,
things don't go so well.

00:32:32.450 --> 00:32:35.221
So you just need to kind of
think the different scenarios

00:32:35.221 --> 00:32:35.720
through.

00:32:39.130 --> 00:32:43.420
We actually had a discussion
earlier today with a VC

00:32:43.420 --> 00:32:45.100
in one of the Bolt companies.

00:32:45.100 --> 00:32:48.610
So do we do a convertible
note deal or an equity deal?

00:32:48.610 --> 00:32:50.120
I could argue either side.

00:32:50.120 --> 00:32:54.840
But maybe as a rule, if you're
talking about raising $250,000,

00:32:54.840 --> 00:32:58.980
$500,000 and you're likely
to raise more money,

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:01.840
like whatever, another
million plus a year

00:33:01.840 --> 00:33:04.590
later, it's not a
bad thing to do.

00:33:04.590 --> 00:33:08.390
It's a quick way to get started,
low legal fees and everything.

00:33:08.390 --> 00:33:14.510
By the time you reach $2 million
or more in convertible note,

00:33:14.510 --> 00:33:17.250
it's just odd.

00:33:17.250 --> 00:33:21.300
There's this amount of money you
have spent that's converting,

00:33:21.300 --> 00:33:22.910
that's going to be dilutive.

00:33:22.910 --> 00:33:24.660
It's starting to be
a biggish amount.

00:33:24.660 --> 00:33:28.890
What if the pre money is
$4 million, let's say.

00:33:28.890 --> 00:33:32.390
Well, already $2 million
converting at $4 million pre,

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:35.080
a third of the company
is already gone.

00:33:35.080 --> 00:33:39.370
So I would say up to $500,000,
a million, $1.5 million maximum.

00:33:39.370 --> 00:33:41.965
If I see a convertible
note at more than that,

00:33:41.965 --> 00:33:44.090
it's probably starting to
get pretty uncomfortable.

00:33:44.090 --> 00:33:45.078
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:52.912 --> 00:33:53.780
AXEL BICHARA: Right.

00:33:53.780 --> 00:33:56.870
Where they would not do it.

00:33:56.870 --> 00:33:59.820
One way to think about
it is, it really depends

00:33:59.820 --> 00:34:01.060
upon the terms of the note.

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:03.630
If you go in and
there's something

00:34:03.630 --> 00:34:05.800
called a cap or no cap.

00:34:05.800 --> 00:34:07.530
Basically a valuation
cap or note.

00:34:07.530 --> 00:34:11.659
So let's say I give you
a note for like 500K

00:34:11.659 --> 00:34:14.239
and it has no cap on
it, so it converts

00:34:14.239 --> 00:34:15.739
in some future financing.

00:34:15.739 --> 00:34:17.300
So you're actually
using my money

00:34:17.300 --> 00:34:20.480
to increase the value of
the company, which I then

00:34:20.480 --> 00:34:21.530
buy shares at.

00:34:21.530 --> 00:34:25.456
So some VCs actually do
that and it's all about

00:34:25.456 --> 00:34:27.580
competing with the next
guy, get a foot in the door

00:34:27.580 --> 00:34:29.699
with some interesting
entrepreneur.

00:34:29.699 --> 00:34:32.790
But from a purely
financial standpoint,

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:35.199
it's actually kind of
crazy to loan somebody

00:34:35.199 --> 00:34:36.909
the money-- it's
typically 2% interest

00:34:36.909 --> 00:34:41.420
rate to increase evaluation,
in which you then invest.

00:34:41.420 --> 00:34:44.134
The other effects-- if
you are a note holder,

00:34:44.134 --> 00:34:45.550
you're actually
not a shareholder.

00:34:45.550 --> 00:34:47.310
So you won't get a board seat.

00:34:47.310 --> 00:34:51.310
So that's one.

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:57.430
But for many investors--
understanding thee objective

00:34:57.430 --> 00:35:00.350
of the investors is
actually important.

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:02.550
Like for many venture
firms especially,

00:35:02.550 --> 00:35:04.425
it's a foot in the door.

00:35:04.425 --> 00:35:08.160
You care about the option
value of doing a deal later.

00:35:08.160 --> 00:35:13.150
So if that's the valuation,
the main objective,

00:35:13.150 --> 00:35:14.370
that's kind of one thing.

00:35:14.370 --> 00:35:20.160
Now if all the money
the company will need

00:35:20.160 --> 00:35:23.130
is let's say $1 million--
it's a bunch of angels

00:35:23.130 --> 00:35:30.550
and they really help you to
work on the deal-- understanding

00:35:30.550 --> 00:35:32.760
the objective is actually
very, very important.

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:35.060
Do you have alignment of
interests or actually conflict

00:35:35.060 --> 00:35:36.600
of interests?

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:38.430
Is the objective
of the investors

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:40.970
to increase your
evaluation or not?

00:35:40.970 --> 00:35:45.740
So there's actually
no simple answer.

00:35:45.740 --> 00:35:48.965
There's something beautiful
about an equity deal.

00:35:48.965 --> 00:35:50.090
You have aligned interests.

00:35:50.090 --> 00:35:53.120
You own more or less--
preferred versus common--

00:35:53.120 --> 00:35:55.840
but it's more or less the
same shares in the company.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:35:59.447
So on the margin, I actually
tend to prefer equity deals.

00:35:59.447 --> 00:36:01.030
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN:
So if I could just

00:36:01.030 --> 00:36:03.100
expand on Axel's comments.

00:36:03.100 --> 00:36:07.320
Remember I said at the beginning
that every form of equity

00:36:07.320 --> 00:36:11.630
has its intended use, it's
benefits and it's costs, right?

00:36:11.630 --> 00:36:15.960
So as Axel said, a note tends
to be a really good instrument

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:19.370
when you are expecting
there to be fairly

00:36:19.370 --> 00:36:21.690
rapid succession of events.

00:36:21.690 --> 00:36:23.550
So you're going to
hit some milestones.

00:36:23.550 --> 00:36:25.990
You expect to
raise more capital.

00:36:25.990 --> 00:36:28.550
It's an opportunity for
you and the investors,

00:36:28.550 --> 00:36:31.240
when your interests
are aligned, to do

00:36:31.240 --> 00:36:32.950
a relatively lightweight deal.

00:36:32.950 --> 00:36:34.490
It's relatively
inexpensive to do.

00:36:34.490 --> 00:36:35.430
It's relatively quick.

00:36:35.430 --> 00:36:37.810
You don't have to
agree on evaluation

00:36:37.810 --> 00:36:40.250
when things are in
flux, which is also

00:36:40.250 --> 00:36:42.190
easier for both parties.

00:36:42.190 --> 00:36:46.180
And the advantage for
you as the founder is you

00:36:46.180 --> 00:36:50.570
haven't already committed a
portion of the company away.

00:36:50.570 --> 00:36:53.210
You have the opportunity
to hit those milestones

00:36:53.210 --> 00:36:56.300
and justify evaluation.

00:36:56.300 --> 00:36:58.060
The advantage for
the investor, again,

00:36:58.060 --> 00:37:00.020
might be the optionality.

00:37:00.020 --> 00:37:02.820
So the option itself
have value to them.

00:37:02.820 --> 00:37:06.600
It might be that they like
the idea that their note will

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:10.030
convert at advantageous
terms in the next round,

00:37:10.030 --> 00:37:14.080
and that's when the cap and
the other terms come in.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:17.880
But again, the purpose
of a note is really

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:21.600
kind of a temporary instrument.

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.425
It's not designed to
be long term instrument

00:37:24.425 --> 00:37:27.090
and it's not intended
to be a kind of one

00:37:27.090 --> 00:37:29.130
off or permanent instrument.

00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:30.780
It comes due.

00:37:30.780 --> 00:37:33.400
It has a termination date.

00:37:33.400 --> 00:37:38.410
So on the date when it matures,
you either have to go back

00:37:38.410 --> 00:37:41.370
and say we need an extension or
you have to pay back that money

00:37:41.370 --> 00:37:44.260
or you have to have a subsequent
funding round in order

00:37:44.260 --> 00:37:46.150
for the note to convert.

00:37:46.150 --> 00:37:48.360
So what you want
to keep in mind is

00:37:48.360 --> 00:37:49.800
that's what it's designed to be.

00:37:49.800 --> 00:37:53.600
It's designed to be
an interim instrument.

00:37:53.600 --> 00:37:56.106
Does that make sense?

00:37:56.106 --> 00:37:58.660
AMIR NASHAT: If I can make
one cautionary statement

00:37:58.660 --> 00:38:00.749
with notes-- in
general, I think if I

00:38:00.749 --> 00:38:02.540
was an entrepreneur
I'd tried to take notes

00:38:02.540 --> 00:38:05.265
if I could, because
I'm paying you Tuesday

00:38:05.265 --> 00:38:07.560
which is in stock for
a hamburger today,

00:38:07.560 --> 00:38:09.126
which is the cash you give me.

00:38:09.126 --> 00:38:10.750
The one thing you
have to watch out for

00:38:10.750 --> 00:38:13.220
is if I gave you
$100,000 in equity

00:38:13.220 --> 00:38:17.600
and I own 5% of your company,
things go sideways whatnot,

00:38:17.600 --> 00:38:18.990
I own 5% of your company.

00:38:18.990 --> 00:38:20.410
So you may not like me.

00:38:20.410 --> 00:38:23.260
We may be in an argument,
but I'm a minor shareholder.

00:38:23.260 --> 00:38:25.070
And most of the controls
is in your hands.

00:38:25.070 --> 00:38:28.610
If the company goes belly
up with it's $100,000 note,

00:38:28.610 --> 00:38:30.430
I'm a creditor
actually, which means

00:38:30.430 --> 00:38:33.110
your intellectual property and
a whole host of other things

00:38:33.110 --> 00:38:36.680
show up in court and I'm first
in line probably, unless you've

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:38.270
taken other loans.

00:38:38.270 --> 00:38:43.000
So my power becomes extremely
strong for the same $100,000.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:44.750
So you really don't
want to screw up

00:38:44.750 --> 00:38:47.860
a note you never
want to borrow money

00:38:47.860 --> 00:38:49.774
when you're close to the edge.

00:38:49.774 --> 00:38:51.940
If you feel really good
about how things are, or you

00:38:51.940 --> 00:38:54.920
do what are called auto
converts, where at your option,

00:38:54.920 --> 00:38:58.315
the note converts to equity, if
investors will give you that.

00:38:58.315 --> 00:38:59.120
A lot of them wont.

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:02.830
But if they allow you to auto
convert at some evaluation,

00:39:02.830 --> 00:39:04.540
then you never really
owe them the money.

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:06.445
It will get converted to equity.

00:39:06.445 --> 00:39:08.137
But be careful about
owing people money,

00:39:08.137 --> 00:39:09.595
because they become
the controllers

00:39:09.595 --> 00:39:11.595
and it's a court process,
which nobody controls.

00:39:16.706 --> 00:39:17.698
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:48.946 --> 00:39:50.890
AMIR NASHAT: How do you
define structural fit

00:39:50.890 --> 00:39:51.520
versus strategic?

00:39:51.520 --> 00:39:52.436
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:14.135 --> 00:40:16.280
AMIR NASHAT: Let me
start with the first part

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:19.610
of your question, which
was the presumption that

00:40:19.610 --> 00:40:21.790
kind of alignment
might be different.

00:40:21.790 --> 00:40:24.020
I think you should be
really careful taking money

00:40:24.020 --> 00:40:28.870
from people where you don't feel
like there's 100% alignment.

00:40:28.870 --> 00:40:31.430
Every one of my
entrepreneurs and I, I hope,

00:40:31.430 --> 00:40:33.980
have the same exact goal.

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:35.650
If you don't, it can
get quite tricky.

00:40:35.650 --> 00:40:37.650
And then in later rounds,
strategics come in,

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:39.790
people come in.

00:40:39.790 --> 00:40:42.830
Maybe objectives
shift a little bit.

00:40:42.830 --> 00:40:44.810
My price point maybe
lower for my stock

00:40:44.810 --> 00:40:47.040
than somebody that led a
very later stage round,

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:50.965
so our sensitivities to certain
events may be different.

00:40:50.965 --> 00:40:52.590
But in general I
think everybody better

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:54.715
be rooting for the same
thing, which is the company

00:40:54.715 --> 00:40:56.100
to be successful.

00:40:56.100 --> 00:40:58.040
And that's one of the
reasons I would always

00:40:58.040 --> 00:41:02.340
worry about people with too
much of a strategic interest.

00:41:02.340 --> 00:41:03.840
Because a lot of
our bio-techs bring

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:07.870
money from corporate partners,
pharmaceutical companies.

00:41:07.870 --> 00:41:11.070
A lot of times they're kind
of interested in the company,

00:41:11.070 --> 00:41:13.900
but they're really interested
in a particular asset.

00:41:13.900 --> 00:41:16.600
And we have to excuse
them from the room

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:18.490
when we have
strategic discussions,

00:41:18.490 --> 00:41:21.605
because we're trying to play
them against other pharma.

00:41:21.605 --> 00:41:23.480
It makes it somewhat of
an awkward situation.

00:41:23.480 --> 00:41:24.940
It's very workable.

00:41:24.940 --> 00:41:27.820
But it's not the same
as having someone

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:30.250
you really trust that you can
just be totally open with.

00:41:30.250 --> 00:41:35.760
So every VC obviously has a
Rolodex, a series of people,

00:41:35.760 --> 00:41:38.390
a network, that they
bring to the table.

00:41:38.390 --> 00:41:41.100
But if you've got a group
that's very, very specifically

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:43.650
interested in a particular
piece of intellectual property

00:41:43.650 --> 00:41:45.840
or a strategic fit or
something like that,

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:48.450
you have to be careful that
your company doesn't drift away

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:50.750
from that or that there aren't
moments where you really

00:41:50.750 --> 00:41:53.006
can't be as frank with
them as you'd like to be.

00:41:55.922 --> 00:41:59.060
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: I think
that's a really lucid answer.

00:41:59.060 --> 00:42:03.640
What I would say is that
people throw around the word

00:42:03.640 --> 00:42:07.230
strategic, and as
you heard just now,

00:42:07.230 --> 00:42:11.380
strategic meant two different
things in the same sentence.

00:42:11.380 --> 00:42:16.720
So the way that I like
to think about it is,

00:42:16.720 --> 00:42:19.790
do we all agree what success is?

00:42:19.790 --> 00:42:22.450
Does success mean the
same thing to all of us?

00:42:22.450 --> 00:42:25.960
How will we know
that we've succeeded?

00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:27.970
And if the answer is
we've gotten $100 million

00:42:27.970 --> 00:42:31.280
or whatever figure it is,
that's not a useful answer,

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:33.590
because there's a semi-infinite
number of trajectories

00:42:33.590 --> 00:42:36.060
that pass through that point.

00:42:36.060 --> 00:42:40.600
So what are the things that we
all care about accomplishing,

00:42:40.600 --> 00:42:47.700
and do we share compatible
ideas about what it will take

00:42:47.700 --> 00:42:50.590
to accomplish that success?

00:42:50.590 --> 00:42:57.000
So in the course of starting
and growing any company,

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.740
you're putting yourself
in, by definition,

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:03.200
a high conflict environment.

00:43:03.200 --> 00:43:06.090
You always have more things
to do than you can do.

00:43:06.090 --> 00:43:08.220
You always have
decisions to make

00:43:08.220 --> 00:43:10.130
in an absence of
complete knowledge,

00:43:10.130 --> 00:43:12.880
so you never have complete
intelligence ever,

00:43:12.880 --> 00:43:15.080
even when you really good
situational awareness,

00:43:15.080 --> 00:43:18.010
you never have
complete intelligence.

00:43:18.010 --> 00:43:22.675
So even when everybody
is really tightly aligned

00:43:22.675 --> 00:43:26.170
and everybody shares the same
objectives, the same goals,

00:43:26.170 --> 00:43:28.150
the same motivations,
you're going

00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:31.370
to have honest
differences of opinion.

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:34.930
If you have divergent
notions of what success is

00:43:34.930 --> 00:43:39.180
or what we care about,
you have a problem.

00:43:39.180 --> 00:43:41.480
You don't just have legitimate
differences of opinion

00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:45.080
about how to solve an
agreed upon problem,

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:48.180
you have different
definitions of the problem.

00:43:48.180 --> 00:43:51.140
That can get very
ugly very quickly,

00:43:51.140 --> 00:43:54.240
and it can just be disaster.

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:57.640
So ultimately what
you really want

00:43:57.640 --> 00:44:00.240
to be sure of is that everybody
on your team, everybody

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:03.420
internally, your
investors, everybody,

00:44:03.420 --> 00:44:05.480
agrees on what success means.

00:44:05.480 --> 00:44:07.850
What do we aim to accomplish?

00:44:07.850 --> 00:44:11.060
How do we win collectively,
all of us together.

00:44:11.060 --> 00:44:12.640
How do we win?

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:15.610
And then you have
the recipe to be

00:44:15.610 --> 00:44:18.930
able to deal with all
of those uncertainties

00:44:18.930 --> 00:44:21.315
and all those decision
points in a productive way.

00:44:25.680 --> 00:44:26.650
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:31.500 --> 00:44:35.692
some sense of what
scale of money

00:44:35.692 --> 00:44:38.989
