ownership as a VC,

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:10.910
but you also help establish--
if you're executing well--

00:47:10.910 --> 00:47:12.830
help establish the
success of the company.

00:47:12.830 --> 00:47:14.870
It would be very
hard for competitors

00:47:14.870 --> 00:47:18.740
to raise money if you have
$100 million into bank already.

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:22.390
So there's all kinds of--
especially sort of in emerging

00:47:22.390 --> 00:47:24.695
winners, you look at, oh,
these are crazy evaluations,

00:47:24.695 --> 00:47:25.770
They're crazy deals.

00:47:25.770 --> 00:47:28.380
If you really look
at it, they may not

00:47:28.380 --> 00:47:30.710
be the crazy if
it is an emerging

00:47:30.710 --> 00:47:34.148
winner in a multi-billion
market disruption, for instance.

00:47:37.892 --> 00:47:43.480
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: So
again, I would say-- sorry.

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:45.805
Again I would say, there
are so many different kinds

00:47:45.805 --> 00:47:46.900
of companies.

00:47:46.900 --> 00:47:49.900
And remember that
we've all commented

00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:53.770
that venture money,
professional money,

00:47:53.770 --> 00:47:59.810
is a very small segment
of company finance.

00:47:59.810 --> 00:48:05.540
So I would say the way I would
answer that is starting from 0,

00:48:05.540 --> 00:48:06.850
the lower end is zero.

00:48:06.850 --> 00:48:09.810
You take no outside money.

00:48:09.810 --> 00:48:11.610
And there have
been companies that

00:48:11.610 --> 00:48:15.600
have famously gone bust after
taking in more than $100

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:17.856
million.

00:48:17.856 --> 00:48:21.780
So there's an
extremely wide range.

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:31.420
The appeal that I think
tends to get overblown

00:48:31.420 --> 00:48:34.350
in a lot of the press
coverage of big deals

00:48:34.350 --> 00:48:35.870
is it sounds very sexy.

00:48:35.870 --> 00:48:36.730
It's very exciting.

00:48:36.730 --> 00:48:38.710
It sounds like a
lot of momentum.

00:48:38.710 --> 00:48:42.880
And that's the intention
of a big round certainly.

00:48:42.880 --> 00:48:47.205
But there's also, again, there
are always costs and always

00:48:47.205 --> 00:48:47.705
downsides.

00:48:47.705 --> 00:48:50.690
The downside is, if you take
a huge amount of capital--

00:48:50.690 --> 00:48:53.450
whether that's hundreds of
millions for $10 million

00:48:53.450 --> 00:48:56.324
depending on your
stage of development--

00:48:56.324 --> 00:48:57.865
if you take a huge
amount of capital,

00:48:57.865 --> 00:49:00.360
it also puts a tremendous
amount of pressure on you

00:49:00.360 --> 00:49:05.240
to use that capital
very aggressively.

00:49:05.240 --> 00:49:08.590
And so companies have
also been blown up

00:49:08.590 --> 00:49:11.380
by taking too much capital.

00:49:11.380 --> 00:49:15.370
So really what you
want to be doing

00:49:15.370 --> 00:49:19.130
is focusing, again,
on Joe's questions.

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:19.830
Whys?

00:49:19.830 --> 00:49:21.610
What are all of the whys?

00:49:21.610 --> 00:49:23.000
Why are you doing this?

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:23.680
Why now?

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:24.960
Why this team?

00:49:24.960 --> 00:49:28.870
Why this amount of money?

00:49:28.870 --> 00:49:31.240
Why this timing?

00:49:31.240 --> 00:49:32.860
Why this instrument?

00:49:32.860 --> 00:49:34.240
Why this firm?

00:49:34.240 --> 00:49:35.320
Whatever.

00:49:35.320 --> 00:49:37.710
Because you really
want to be focused on

00:49:37.710 --> 00:49:41.910
is this the right amount
of money for my company

00:49:41.910 --> 00:49:45.950
to do what it is intended
to do at this point in time?

00:49:49.050 --> 00:49:54.878
It's really easy to get
wildly out of balance there.

00:49:54.878 --> 00:49:55.790
AMIR NASHAT: Yeah.

00:49:55.790 --> 00:50:01.090
I mean, again, we write checks
as small as $50,000, $100,000

00:50:01.090 --> 00:50:02.540
to get started.

00:50:02.540 --> 00:50:05.716
Our goal is probably $5
million to say $20 million

00:50:05.716 --> 00:50:07.340
in an investment.

00:50:07.340 --> 00:50:08.090
It's a wide range.

00:50:08.090 --> 00:50:09.798
If the company only
ever needs $1 million

00:50:09.798 --> 00:50:12.890
and we all know
that going into it,

00:50:12.890 --> 00:50:14.810
it's probably not a
fit for us, because we

00:50:14.810 --> 00:50:16.518
have a reasonably
large fund so we'd have

00:50:16.518 --> 00:50:17.890
to make so many small bets.

00:50:17.890 --> 00:50:20.320
It's perfectly fine if a
company only takes $1 million

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:23.380
and is either successful
or unsuccessful.

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:25.230
Because we all learned
in a very quick way

00:50:25.230 --> 00:50:27.110
that it was really great.

00:50:27.110 --> 00:50:30.090
You're never going to complain
if you took $1 million

00:50:30.090 --> 00:50:32.480
and turn it into a big win.

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:35.580
I have had a lot of co-investors
who complain about that.

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:37.290
But my view is, come on.

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:39.070
You've got to be kidding me.

00:50:39.070 --> 00:50:40.890
And then of course
we kind of sometimes

00:50:40.890 --> 00:50:42.890
have to plan to put 20,
30 million hours through

00:50:42.890 --> 00:50:44.750
to support our company.

00:50:44.750 --> 00:50:48.130
I think the fundamental
question is exactly the why.

00:50:48.130 --> 00:50:53.960
And for us, we are so focused
on backing entrepreneurs,

00:50:53.960 --> 00:50:56.950
every single deal we've
been in pretty much,

00:50:56.950 --> 00:50:59.450
the intellectual
property shifted.

00:50:59.450 --> 00:51:01.990
Almost everything
about the deal changed.

00:51:01.990 --> 00:51:04.500
Very rarely does it work
exactly the way you want.

00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:06.130
The people are what
make it happen.

00:51:06.130 --> 00:51:08.930
And if a person doesn't
own a lot of it,

00:51:08.930 --> 00:51:11.210
then why are they coming
to work every day?

00:51:11.210 --> 00:51:14.840
So I think whenever we own a
venture entrepreneurial type

00:51:14.840 --> 00:51:18.050
deal, whenever we
own a lot of company,

00:51:18.050 --> 00:51:20.090
something went horribly wrong.

00:51:20.090 --> 00:51:23.912
And when we don't own a lot of
it and it's a great company,

00:51:23.912 --> 00:51:26.120
something's going great
because they're raising money

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:27.120
at great valuations.

00:51:27.120 --> 00:51:29.036
They don't need the money
to bring capital in.

00:51:29.036 --> 00:51:30.610
They give a shit about stock.

00:51:30.610 --> 00:51:32.120
They don't want
to give it to me.

00:51:32.120 --> 00:51:33.740
They don't want to
give it to anybody.

00:51:33.740 --> 00:51:36.500
They're going to charge a lot of
money for that share of stock.

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:38.360
That's the best kinds
of deals we're in.

00:51:38.360 --> 00:51:40.880
Whenever we own
75% of a startup,

00:51:40.880 --> 00:51:42.761
of a venture backed
company, it's

00:51:42.761 --> 00:51:44.510
because we had to
bridge them three times,

00:51:44.510 --> 00:51:46.630
they had terrible financings.

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:50.835
So I love it when entrepreneurs
say, I don't need your money.

00:51:50.835 --> 00:51:52.400
I'll do it some other way.

00:51:52.400 --> 00:51:54.520
I'll just take a little bit.

00:51:54.520 --> 00:51:56.410
Again, it puts you in
a precarious position.

00:51:56.410 --> 00:51:57.910
But it's exactly
what Julianne said,

00:51:57.910 --> 00:52:00.241
which is once you raise
$100 million dollars,

00:52:00.241 --> 00:52:02.240
you need to generate $200
million, $300 million,

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:04.490
$400 million dollars
worth of exit

00:52:04.490 --> 00:52:06.227
to keep your investors happy.

00:52:06.227 --> 00:52:07.310
They're all on your board.

00:52:07.310 --> 00:52:10.220
They're not going to let you
go down a path that's small.

00:52:10.220 --> 00:52:12.730
So your flexibility just
went out the window.

00:52:12.730 --> 00:52:15.270
They're going to push
you down a path that's

00:52:15.270 --> 00:52:19.682
big return, big win, and that
may not be what you want to do.

00:52:19.682 --> 00:52:22.050
PROFESSOR: Let me--
in the materials,

00:52:22.050 --> 00:52:25.404
there's a PowerPoint
on beginner's guide

00:52:25.404 --> 00:52:26.195
to venture capital.

00:52:26.195 --> 00:52:29.480
And if you haven't read it, you
should have before the class.

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:31.360
But these guys
compete for capital

00:52:31.360 --> 00:52:33.210
to invest in their funds.

00:52:33.210 --> 00:52:36.780
And they have to show a return
history to the people that

00:52:36.780 --> 00:52:38.330
are going to invest in them.

00:52:38.330 --> 00:52:43.550
And one of the issues is that
when these guys put money

00:52:43.550 --> 00:52:46.670
in your company, that's
when the stopwatch starts

00:52:46.670 --> 00:52:49.110
on how fast are they
generating return.

00:52:49.110 --> 00:52:51.770
So you've got to
be prepared to have

00:52:51.770 --> 00:52:54.110
everything running
as fast as you can

00:52:54.110 --> 00:52:55.510
once that money comes in.

00:52:55.510 --> 00:52:57.676
And they're going to push
you to it, because they've

00:52:57.676 --> 00:53:00.780
got to turn around and say, to
their investors, you gave us X

00:53:00.780 --> 00:53:05.940
and we returned so
much time X. So even

00:53:05.940 --> 00:53:08.750
if you can convince them
to invest in your company,

00:53:08.750 --> 00:53:10.450
if you're not ready
to run like crazy,

00:53:10.450 --> 00:53:13.110
if you don't have a model
that you think could work,

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:15.150
pedal to the floor,
it's going to be

00:53:15.150 --> 00:53:17.440
a tension filled environment.

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:18.420
Would you disagree?

00:53:18.420 --> 00:53:20.480
AXEL BICHARA: I
would probably agree.

