All right.

00:53:30.161 --> 00:53:31.155
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:30.298 --> 00:54:32.099
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN:
Well, so first of all--

00:54:32.099 --> 00:54:34.390
PROFESSOR: Maybe generalize
it so you could work it in.

00:54:34.390 --> 00:54:36.264
I was going to ask a
variation of that, which

00:54:36.264 --> 00:54:39.050
is what are the biggest problems
you see for people trying

00:54:39.050 --> 00:54:41.466
to raise money, because that's
sort of what you're saying.

00:54:41.466 --> 00:54:43.152
I don't really
understand how they're--

00:54:43.152 --> 00:54:44.136
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:05.224 --> 00:55:07.140
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: So
here's the first thing.

00:55:07.140 --> 00:55:09.176
Or actually here's
the zero thing.

00:55:09.176 --> 00:55:16.600
The zero thing is you really
need to have not just exchanges

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:18.870
like this, but you need to
have meaningful exchanges

00:55:18.870 --> 00:55:20.865
with someone who's
a mentor to you who

00:55:20.865 --> 00:55:26.520
can give you ongoing
sanity checks and guidance.

00:55:26.520 --> 00:55:29.130
This is my plug for the MIT
venture mentoring service.

00:55:29.130 --> 00:55:30.560
It is the most amazing thing.

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:31.760
It is free to you.

00:55:31.760 --> 00:55:33.420
Go sign up right now.

00:55:33.420 --> 00:55:34.590
I mean, seriously.

00:55:34.590 --> 00:55:36.120
Do not wait.

00:55:36.120 --> 00:55:36.810
Immediately.

00:55:36.810 --> 00:55:39.750
Go immediately.

00:55:39.750 --> 00:55:42.340
The premise of the venture
mentoring service is that these

00:55:42.340 --> 00:55:48.640
amazing people, Joe included,
will spend time with you

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:54.790
to advise you and, under
the terms of the program,

00:55:54.790 --> 00:55:58.820
cannot take any interest
in your business.

00:55:58.820 --> 00:56:01.800
And so it's purely
objective advice.

00:56:01.800 --> 00:56:05.535
It's in your interest, not even
in the business's interests,

00:56:05.535 --> 00:56:08.550
it's advising you
personally as founder.

00:56:08.550 --> 00:56:11.360
So go get that.

00:56:11.360 --> 00:56:15.580
The first thing then
after that is, forgive me

00:56:15.580 --> 00:56:17.580
if I'm reading too much
into your question,

00:56:17.580 --> 00:56:20.480
but it sounds like you've
already have some tensions that

00:56:20.480 --> 00:56:23.400
have already started.

00:56:23.400 --> 00:56:24.770
That's a warning sign.

00:56:24.770 --> 00:56:26.245
Klaxon's are going off.

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:32.470
If you already have significant
frictions with someone

00:56:32.470 --> 00:56:37.515
and you haven't even made a
financial transaction yet,

00:56:37.515 --> 00:56:39.140
I think you want to
step back and think

00:56:39.140 --> 00:56:41.450
about where those
frictions are coming from.

00:56:41.450 --> 00:56:47.610
Are they coming from legitimate
discussion points, things

00:56:47.610 --> 00:56:49.770
that you're being challenged
to think about that

00:56:49.770 --> 00:56:53.630
are in the interest of the
company you're founding,

00:56:53.630 --> 00:56:55.750
or are they personal frictions?

00:56:55.750 --> 00:56:59.070
Are they differences,
again, in objectives?

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:01.720
What's behind those frictions?

00:57:01.720 --> 00:57:04.250
And are those
productive frictions?

00:57:04.250 --> 00:57:08.770
So both of my fellow
panelists have

00:57:08.770 --> 00:57:12.557
spoken about the
beneficial frictions

00:57:12.557 --> 00:57:14.015
that you can
encounter, whether its

00:57:14.015 --> 00:57:22.400
from peers or from advisers and
investors and incubator staff

00:57:22.400 --> 00:57:24.260
pushing, pulling, tugging.

00:57:24.260 --> 00:57:26.880
Those can be
productive frictions.

00:57:26.880 --> 00:57:28.640
But if you're
actually experiencing

00:57:28.640 --> 00:57:31.820
a lot of discomfort, I think
you should listen to that.

00:57:34.550 --> 00:57:35.532
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:50.262 --> 00:57:54.055
AXEL BICHARA: I have--
it really depends

00:57:54.055 --> 00:57:55.180
on who you're working with.

00:57:55.180 --> 00:57:59.400
But I'll answer your question
in a slightly different way.

00:57:59.400 --> 00:58:02.200
When an investor funds
you, they probably

00:58:02.200 --> 00:58:03.590
make a whole bunch of calls.

00:58:03.590 --> 00:58:04.637
Who are you?

00:58:04.637 --> 00:58:05.720
What have you done before?

00:58:05.720 --> 00:58:07.053
What's it like to work with you?

00:58:07.053 --> 00:58:10.480
I'm often amazed how few
entrepreneurs actually

00:58:10.480 --> 00:58:11.850
check out the investors.

00:58:11.850 --> 00:58:16.020
So if you take somebody on
your board as a lead investor,

00:58:16.020 --> 00:58:20.090
call up three, four CEOs
they worked with before.

00:58:20.090 --> 00:58:24.140
I mean, I would say it's almost
irresponsible not to do it.

00:58:24.140 --> 00:58:27.210
And it's not just,
oh, they're nice guys.

00:58:27.210 --> 00:58:28.210
Do they have a Rolodex?

00:58:28.210 --> 00:58:30.990
It's what happens when things
get difficult. Because they

00:58:30.990 --> 00:58:37.460
will get difficult. How
have they behaved in follow

00:58:37.460 --> 00:58:41.410
on financings, in work
with strategic investors,

00:58:41.410 --> 00:58:44.566
at exit, management
team building.

00:58:44.566 --> 00:58:47.080
If there's a problem
with a founder/CEO,

00:58:47.080 --> 00:58:50.990
how do they behave under
those circumstances.

00:58:50.990 --> 00:58:54.810
So just do the reference checks.

00:58:54.810 --> 00:58:57.930
Because as I said earlier,
they can fire you,

00:58:57.930 --> 00:58:59.160
but you can't fire them.

00:59:02.856 --> 00:59:05.430
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: Did
that answer your question?

00:59:05.430 --> 00:59:06.402
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:15.116 --> 00:59:16.740
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN:
Mechanically, there

00:59:16.740 --> 00:59:18.950
are only three ways
that anybody gets deals.

00:59:18.950 --> 00:59:21.960
You go out and get them,
you get referred to them

00:59:21.960 --> 00:59:25.900
by peers and folks
in your network,

00:59:25.900 --> 00:59:29.171
or you get cold submissions.

00:59:29.171 --> 00:59:29.670
That's it.

00:59:29.670 --> 00:59:31.730
There are three mechanisms.

00:59:31.730 --> 00:59:33.290
Different firms
have different ways

00:59:33.290 --> 00:59:36.870
of going out and getting them.

00:59:36.870 --> 00:59:40.400
And by and large,
the return on effort

00:59:40.400 --> 00:59:46.150
for an entrepreneur for a
cold submission is pretty low.

00:59:46.150 --> 00:59:50.040
So if you're
someone thinking you

00:59:50.040 --> 00:59:53.660
want to raise venture
funds at any scale,

00:59:53.660 --> 00:59:59.780
it's in your interest to go see
who looks like the most likely

00:59:59.780 --> 01:00:02.860
best fit for you and go
find a way to meet them.

01:00:05.430 --> 01:00:08.760
But really ultimately it's
important recognize that those

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:10.460
are the only three channels.

01:00:10.460 --> 01:00:12.210
There aren't any other channels.

01:00:12.210 --> 01:00:15.455
Does that make sense?

01:00:15.455 --> 01:00:18.750
PROFESSOR: What role
do introductions have?

01:00:18.750 --> 01:00:21.070
Referrals?

01:00:21.070 --> 01:00:23.435
Entrepreneurs should be
building a full team of people.

01:00:23.435 --> 01:00:28.829
Is that an important part
of who surrounds them

01:00:28.829 --> 01:00:29.620
in your experience?

01:00:29.620 --> 01:00:31.703
AXEL BICHARA: Wait, this
seems to be to questions.

01:00:31.703 --> 01:00:33.182
Is a referral or the--

01:00:33.182 --> 01:00:36.040
PROFESSOR: In other words,
having a deal referred to you,

01:00:36.040 --> 01:00:40.040
is that elevated higher in the
stack if you know the person

01:00:40.040 --> 01:00:43.890
and how does an entrepreneur
who doesn't-- get into that

01:00:43.890 --> 01:00:44.390
network?

01:00:44.390 --> 01:00:45.510
Any advice on that?

01:00:45.510 --> 01:00:48.670
AXEL BICHARA: Well, I would say
certainly anybody in this room

01:00:48.670 --> 01:00:51.580
should be able to get an
introduction to any of us

01:00:51.580 --> 01:00:53.080
with-- I mean, it
should be trivial.

01:00:53.080 --> 01:00:55.910
It's really not that hard at
all to get good introductions

01:00:55.910 --> 01:00:58.334
and they absolutely do matter.

01:00:58.334 --> 01:01:00.500
And there's some that are
good, some that are great,

01:01:00.500 --> 01:01:01.930
some that are not so good.

01:01:01.930 --> 01:01:05.180
But a lot of it is through
networking, who do you know,

01:01:05.180 --> 01:01:09.240
and you absolutely want
to pursue investors

01:01:09.240 --> 01:01:10.550
through strong introductions.

01:01:10.550 --> 01:01:11.650
It's a no-brainer.

01:01:11.650 --> 01:01:12.620
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:34.899 --> 01:01:36.670
AMIR NASHAT: I'll
take that, I guess.

01:01:36.670 --> 01:01:41.090
It just really depends
on-- in the Langor Lab,

01:01:41.090 --> 01:01:46.300
we used to have a formula
which was science--

01:01:46.300 --> 01:01:48.780
you publish the paper in
science, you file the IP,

01:01:48.780 --> 01:01:49.890
and you have animal data.

01:01:49.890 --> 01:01:51.940
You're ready to roll.

01:01:51.940 --> 01:01:53.420
That works in general.

01:01:53.420 --> 01:02:02.900
But I think I think that there's
a point at which the technology

01:02:02.900 --> 01:02:05.870
and innovation stops being
a series of questions

01:02:05.870 --> 01:02:08.340
and it starts being
a series of answers.

01:02:08.340 --> 01:02:10.060
And I think what you
find is that that's

01:02:10.060 --> 01:02:13.130
a good transition wherever
people who in academia like

01:02:13.130 --> 01:02:16.580
to ask questions are no longer
really interested in pursuing

01:02:16.580 --> 01:02:17.380
that.

01:02:17.380 --> 01:02:19.280
And what companies
like to do is create

01:02:19.280 --> 01:02:23.730
answers-- a technical
translation of concept

01:02:23.730 --> 01:02:25.130
into a product.

01:02:25.130 --> 01:02:27.570
And the rigorous-ness
of the precision

01:02:27.570 --> 01:02:29.200
of the answers and
all those things

01:02:29.200 --> 01:02:30.526
becomes really important.

01:02:30.526 --> 01:02:31.650
And it just becomes boring.

01:02:31.650 --> 01:02:33.566
It's very hard to get a
grad student to do it,

01:02:33.566 --> 01:02:34.570
for a postdoc to do it.

01:02:34.570 --> 01:02:37.940
So I think that tends to be the
point at which it kind of hits

01:02:37.940 --> 01:02:39.570
a stalling point
in whether it then

01:02:39.570 --> 01:02:42.380
finds a home on the other
side where a group of people

01:02:42.380 --> 01:02:44.130
say, yeah, this could
easily be a product.

01:02:44.130 --> 01:02:44.950
Let's go for it.

01:02:44.950 --> 01:02:46.500
It's worth being a product.

01:02:46.500 --> 01:02:47.750
It'll either sink or swim.

01:02:47.750 --> 01:02:50.430
But I think I've always--
at least in the lab,

01:02:50.430 --> 01:02:53.549
you could see a
trajectory of a project

01:02:53.549 --> 01:02:55.090
just stop being
interesting to people

01:02:55.090 --> 01:02:58.130
because the next steps
were kind of doing it

01:02:58.130 --> 01:03:01.040
100 times to get the
quality control levels right

01:03:01.040 --> 01:03:01.832
or what not.

01:03:01.832 --> 01:03:04.210
To do a lot of animal
work just wasn't

01:03:04.210 --> 01:03:05.290
that interesting anymore.

01:03:05.290 --> 01:03:09.591
So that's when we typically
tried to kick it out.

01:03:09.591 --> 01:03:10.090
Yeah.

01:03:10.090 --> 01:03:17.760
When the questions become--
I think that curious people

01:03:17.760 --> 01:03:20.050
love unpredictability.

01:03:20.050 --> 01:03:24.200
And I think that scientists love
unpredictability in the data.

01:03:24.200 --> 01:03:25.620
Every experiment
you do, you find

01:03:25.620 --> 01:03:27.250
something you thought
was going to do X

01:03:27.250 --> 01:03:28.500
and it's not going to do that.

01:03:28.500 --> 01:03:30.720
I think that's a very hard
way to make a product.

01:03:30.720 --> 01:03:32.990
I think that's kind of a
good scientific discovery.

01:03:32.990 --> 01:03:35.030
I think at some point
then it becomes a series

01:03:35.030 --> 01:03:36.590
of business unpredictabilities.

01:03:36.590 --> 01:03:38.440
Can we raise the money?

01:03:38.440 --> 01:03:40.330
And so I think
when it transitions

01:03:40.330 --> 01:03:43.010
from being a science
experiment to being technology

01:03:43.010 --> 01:03:45.195
is kind of when you
go from questions

01:03:45.195 --> 01:03:47.321
to answers in my mind.

01:03:47.321 --> 01:03:49.085
I don't know how others--

01:03:49.085 --> 01:03:53.540
AXEL BICHARA: I would answer
it slightly differently

01:03:53.540 --> 01:04:00.600
in that there's so many
potential investors out there.

01:04:00.600 --> 01:04:04.167
And I guess my view is more
from a software, hardware tech

01:04:04.167 --> 01:04:05.625
company, not so
much life sciences.

01:04:08.270 --> 01:04:13.120
By networking with potential
investors from early on,

01:04:13.120 --> 01:04:16.230
you're likely to create
value in what you're doing

01:04:16.230 --> 01:04:20.160
and that could be helping
validate technology or not,

01:04:20.160 --> 01:04:22.404
finding competition.

01:04:22.404 --> 01:04:23.320
It's just interesting.

01:04:23.320 --> 01:04:24.306
What's a body language?

01:04:24.306 --> 01:04:25.680
Do you have really
short meetings

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:29.050
or are there people
leaning forward and wanting

01:04:29.050 --> 01:04:31.864
to spend more time with you?

01:04:31.864 --> 01:04:33.530
Every entrepreneur
needs to build a team

01:04:33.530 --> 01:04:34.430
from the beginning.

01:04:34.430 --> 01:04:38.810
I think value added
investors have great networks

01:04:38.810 --> 01:04:43.310
and may give you feedback
on where there at the holes

01:04:43.310 --> 01:04:46.127
in your team and maybe
make introductions.

01:04:46.127 --> 01:04:47.585
Some of the best
deals I've done is

01:04:47.585 --> 01:04:49.668
I ended up introducing the
founders to each other.

01:04:52.056 --> 01:04:53.680
That doesn't happen
to you if you don't

01:04:53.680 --> 01:04:54.860
go out and talk to people.

01:04:54.860 --> 01:04:59.730
So I would say, if in doubt, I
would start turning financing

01:04:59.730 --> 01:05:00.750
sources earlier.

01:05:00.750 --> 01:05:02.880
That doesn't mean
you do a big pitch

01:05:02.880 --> 01:05:04.330
and set up a meeting
at a VC firm.

01:05:04.330 --> 01:05:06.639
That's let's grab a
coffee at a Starbucks

01:05:06.639 --> 01:05:08.430
with somebody who has
some domain knowledge

01:05:08.430 --> 01:05:09.812
and get some feedback.

01:05:09.812 --> 01:05:10.804
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:05:26.676 --> 01:05:29.300
AMIR NASHAT: What's
the triple one?

01:05:29.300 --> 01:05:30.785
What's the double?

01:05:30.785 --> 01:05:31.775
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:05:54.730 --> 01:05:58.280
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN:
So this is again

01:05:58.280 --> 01:06:00.295
one of those it depends
kind of answers.

01:06:03.290 --> 01:06:06.800
The first thing that I
think you have to recognize

01:06:06.800 --> 01:06:11.940
is that by declaring that
you have multiple objectives,

01:06:11.940 --> 01:06:15.060
you've set yourself
a much harder task.

01:06:15.060 --> 01:06:17.090
That doesn't mean
it's not worth doing.

01:06:17.090 --> 01:06:19.930
But the point is, from the
get go, you've set yourself

01:06:19.930 --> 01:06:24.200
a very challenging proposition.

01:06:24.200 --> 01:06:27.560
And there is a much
smaller segment

01:06:27.560 --> 01:06:32.870
of investors who are interested
in that kind of proposition.

01:06:32.870 --> 01:06:35.730
Most of them are not
here on the east coast.

01:06:35.730 --> 01:06:40.220
It's not that there aren't
any, but most of them are not.

01:06:40.220 --> 01:06:42.380
You will find
congregations of them

01:06:42.380 --> 01:06:48.250
at places like SoCap, the
Social Capital Conference.

01:06:48.250 --> 01:06:54.670
You'll find them at
places similar to that.

01:06:54.670 --> 01:06:56.970
There are foundations
that are beginning

01:06:56.970 --> 01:07:03.250
to do some investment because
they may want to see a return,

01:07:03.250 --> 01:07:05.410
but they don't have to.

01:07:05.410 --> 01:07:09.720
So Omidyar for example is one.

01:07:09.720 --> 01:07:11.350
Domini is one.

01:07:11.350 --> 01:07:14.790
There are several like that.

01:07:14.790 --> 01:07:18.520
The Kahn foundation does some.

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:26.780
But again, you're
talking about seeking out

01:07:26.780 --> 01:07:30.070
investors who are a very
tiny sliver of an already

01:07:30.070 --> 01:07:31.190
small pool.

01:07:31.190 --> 01:07:33.520
So it just makes
it incumbent on you

01:07:33.520 --> 01:07:36.360
to be that much more focused
about really seeking out

01:07:36.360 --> 01:07:40.350
investors who are interested
in your specific proposition.

01:07:40.350 --> 01:07:43.910
Not double bottom line or
triple bottom line investors,

01:07:43.910 --> 01:07:48.580
but people who have
declared publicly

01:07:48.580 --> 01:07:53.040
that they are interested in
whatever it is you're doing.

01:07:53.040 --> 01:07:57.940
Because it really is a
very, very narrow segment.

01:07:57.940 --> 01:08:00.340
The good news I would
say is that there

01:08:00.340 --> 01:08:03.500
is a lot more happening
in that segment of late.

01:08:03.500 --> 01:08:05.630
It's very disorganized.

01:08:05.630 --> 01:08:08.270
Extremely disorganized.

01:08:08.270 --> 01:08:13.310
And you'll find that there are
even more, on a relative scale,

01:08:13.310 --> 01:08:15.970
there are even more people
looking for that capital

01:08:15.970 --> 01:08:20.917
than there are looking for
conventional venture money,

01:08:20.917 --> 01:08:21.750
whatever that means.

01:08:24.420 --> 01:08:26.660
So it's challenging.

01:08:26.660 --> 01:08:30.359
It's not impossible, but
it's really incumbent on you.

01:08:30.359 --> 01:08:33.569
You need to be very,
very focused in targeting

01:08:33.569 --> 01:08:36.142
exactly the right folks.

01:08:36.142 --> 01:08:37.850
That's the last thing
I'll say about that

01:08:37.850 --> 01:08:42.760
is that there are some
really good groups to join

01:08:42.760 --> 01:08:47.040
if you haven't already--
again, to share peer knowledge.

01:08:47.040 --> 01:08:51.910
So the social entrepreneurship
groups, for example,

01:08:51.910 --> 01:08:55.189
are really, really
worth being involved

01:08:55.189 --> 01:08:58.904
in to share intelligence
with peer companies

01:08:58.904 --> 01:09:02.510
so that you can
help each other out.

01:09:02.510 --> 01:09:04.420
AMIR NASHAT: If I can
make a comment on it.

01:09:04.420 --> 01:09:07.100
Again, I'm going
to color my comment

01:09:07.100 --> 01:09:09.670
by saying that I invest in
biotech and health care stuff

01:09:09.670 --> 01:09:12.149
primarily.

01:09:12.149 --> 01:09:15.359
I find this whole concept of
double, triple, and quadruple,

01:09:15.359 --> 01:09:17.330
and I'm sure people make
up more bottom lines

01:09:17.330 --> 01:09:20.750
to be kind of
intellectually-- like it

01:09:20.750 --> 01:09:24.069
lacks intellectual rigor.

01:09:24.069 --> 01:09:26.729
Without question, every
single person I've backed,

01:09:26.729 --> 01:09:28.779
especially in the
health care area,

01:09:28.779 --> 01:09:32.319
is not doing what they're
doing to make money.

01:09:32.319 --> 01:09:35.300
They're doing what they're
doing to make a huge impact.

01:09:35.300 --> 01:09:39.000
If you want to make an
apology for not making

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:42.430
a huge impact by
saying, well, I'm

01:09:42.430 --> 01:09:43.640
going to do some other stuff.

01:09:43.640 --> 01:09:45.770
I've got these
multiple objectives.

01:09:45.770 --> 01:09:48.880
They've got one objective,
which is to cure that disease.

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:52.020
The faster they can cure it
with the least amount of money,

01:09:52.020 --> 01:09:56.150
with the fastest amount of time,
the most efficient way to do it

01:09:56.150 --> 01:09:59.700
is in the benefit
of the patient.

01:09:59.700 --> 01:10:02.280
And so what you find
is that if you then

01:10:02.280 --> 01:10:04.800
want to treat the most
number of patients

01:10:04.800 --> 01:10:07.460
with that medicine
or that approach,

01:10:07.460 --> 01:10:09.170
the most efficient
business model

01:10:09.170 --> 01:10:11.320
which creates the greatest
profitability, which

01:10:11.320 --> 01:10:13.850
allows the maximum
amount of sharing

01:10:13.850 --> 01:10:15.660
of value between the
person that gains

01:10:15.660 --> 01:10:18.199
the benefit and the person
who provided the benefit

01:10:18.199 --> 01:10:19.240
is the best way to do it.

01:10:19.240 --> 01:10:22.437
And when you look
at even in places

01:10:22.437 --> 01:10:24.270
where social entrepreneurship
is a big deal,

01:10:24.270 --> 01:10:27.150
I think when you'll find
ideas that really take off,

01:10:27.150 --> 01:10:29.200
it's because there's a
sustainability to them.

01:10:29.200 --> 01:10:31.410
The person that
receives the benefit

01:10:31.410 --> 01:10:33.630
is willing to share that
benefit with the person that

01:10:33.630 --> 01:10:34.430
provides it.

01:10:34.430 --> 01:10:38.540
And I think this idea that we're
going to skimp on all of that

01:10:38.540 --> 01:10:40.900
and not come up with a
business model that's

01:10:40.900 --> 01:10:43.880
the best alignment of
everyone's interests

01:10:43.880 --> 01:10:46.990
is to me where I kind of
get lost in the whole thing.

01:10:46.990 --> 01:10:51.320
I feel like usually when you
have these situations where

01:10:51.320 --> 01:10:54.267
you're kind of compromising,
I suppose-- because every time

01:10:54.267 --> 01:10:56.600
someone said double or triple
bottom line, which I'm not

01:10:56.600 --> 01:10:59.030
implying is your
case, it feels to me

01:10:59.030 --> 01:11:01.420
like a compromise versus
saying, let's align

01:11:01.420 --> 01:11:05.944
the interests of the farmer in
the village who doesn't have

01:11:05.944 --> 01:11:07.360
enough money for
the weather data,

01:11:07.360 --> 01:11:09.110
but they've got interest
in other things--

01:11:09.110 --> 01:11:11.180
let's find a way to
make it a win-win-win

01:11:11.180 --> 01:11:13.910
and really line up
everybody's interest.

01:11:13.910 --> 01:11:16.160
And then it becomes
actually only one objective,

01:11:16.160 --> 01:11:19.390
which is maximum impact for
everybody in the equation.

01:11:19.390 --> 01:11:22.025
So I don't like the idea
that it's compromise.

01:11:22.025 --> 01:11:25.000
And so maybe it's
colored by health care

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:27.301
and maybe my tech partners
wouldn't necessarily

01:11:27.301 --> 01:11:28.300
view the world that way.

01:11:28.300 --> 01:11:30.420
But in every one of our
health care companies,

01:11:30.420 --> 01:11:32.950
everyone's only got one
objective-- cure that kid

01:11:32.950 --> 01:11:35.640
or make that impact.

01:11:35.640 --> 01:11:37.740
And the money is just
part of the whole equation

01:11:37.740 --> 01:11:40.460
to make it as efficient,
the Carnot efficiency

01:11:40.460 --> 01:11:41.780
of the idea basically.

01:11:41.780 --> 01:11:44.820
Just get it as perfect
as you can to line it up.

01:11:44.820 --> 01:11:46.819
So that's kind of
the way I do it.

01:11:46.819 --> 01:11:49.110
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN: I think
you should get extra points

01:11:49.110 --> 01:11:52.780
for saying Carnot efficiency
in a discussion about finance.

01:11:52.780 --> 01:11:55.720
This is how we
know we're at MIT.

01:11:55.720 --> 01:11:57.119
We're geeks.

01:11:57.119 --> 01:11:58.660
AMIR NASHAT: Everybody
understood it.

01:11:58.660 --> 01:12:00.620
No one was not understanding it.

01:12:00.620 --> 01:12:03.280
PROFESSOR: It's on a
cheat sheet beforehand.

01:12:03.280 --> 01:12:06.070
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:06.070 --> 01:12:07.567
What about with
all the different--

01:12:07.567 --> 01:12:09.108
AMIR NASHAT: They
don't use that word

01:12:09.108 --> 01:12:10.471
at Harvard, that's for sure.

01:12:10.471 --> 01:12:12.279
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:12.279 --> 01:12:14.070
PROFESSOR: With all
the different financing

01:12:14.070 --> 01:12:17.500
sources that are out now
with crowdfunding coming on

01:12:17.500 --> 01:12:21.990
and the traditional friends
and family and everything,

01:12:21.990 --> 01:12:26.090
can you talk a little bit about
mismatch of investor groups?

01:12:26.090 --> 01:12:27.720
Have you seen deals
that were really

01:12:27.720 --> 01:12:31.280
good deals but they got
the wrong initial investors

01:12:31.280 --> 01:12:33.720
and you can't work
with them and you pass?

01:12:33.720 --> 01:12:38.490
What kind of watch
words would you

01:12:38.490 --> 01:12:41.390
have for people about
how they approach that?

01:12:41.390 --> 01:12:43.100
Is that a common mistake?

01:12:43.100 --> 01:12:45.820
Or anyway, just can
you comment on that?

01:12:45.820 --> 01:12:46.465
Anybody?

01:12:46.465 --> 01:12:48.910
AXEL BICHARA: I can
start with a few.

01:12:48.910 --> 01:12:53.049
The most classic
is-- well, I guess

01:12:53.049 --> 01:12:55.090
the two classic ones that
jump to mind right away

01:12:55.090 --> 01:12:59.510
are amount of capital
relative to the opportunity,

01:12:59.510 --> 01:13:06.310
where you're going after some
marketable opportunity which

01:13:06.310 --> 01:13:09.870
turns out to be kind of narrow,
but you've raised so much money

01:13:09.870 --> 01:13:13.220
that you kind of need to
assume a level of success

01:13:13.220 --> 01:13:14.720
that the market
will just not yield.

01:13:14.720 --> 01:13:17.000
These are the worst deals.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:19.250
And the conflict may
not happen immediately,

01:13:19.250 --> 01:13:21.560
but it happens over time.

01:13:21.560 --> 01:13:24.740
So being realistic about the
potential of the market you're

01:13:24.740 --> 01:13:26.280
going after and
raising the capital

01:13:26.280 --> 01:13:29.924
to really pursue the upset
over time, but not all upfront

01:13:29.924 --> 01:13:31.590
because you think the
stars will line up

01:13:31.590 --> 01:13:34.810
in terms of what you pursue.

01:13:34.810 --> 01:13:38.940
Some of the worst deals I've
done had exactly that problem.

01:13:38.940 --> 01:13:41.170
The other one--
strategic investors.

01:13:41.170 --> 01:13:42.980
Strategic investors,
by definition,

01:13:42.980 --> 01:13:45.230
have a strategic
interests and not

01:13:45.230 --> 01:13:47.740
primarily a financial interest.

01:13:47.740 --> 01:13:51.610
And just think about how long
it takes to build a company.

01:13:51.610 --> 01:13:55.090
I would say most
overnight successes

01:13:55.090 --> 01:13:56.830
took 10 years to get there.

01:13:56.830 --> 01:13:58.710
So let's say there's
a 10 year time frame

01:13:58.710 --> 01:14:00.690
to build a great company.

01:14:00.690 --> 01:14:02.770
During those 10 years,
whoever did the deal

01:14:02.770 --> 01:14:04.210
from the strategic
investor, which

01:14:04.210 --> 01:14:06.920
is often a biz deaf, culp
deaf person, whatever.

01:14:06.920 --> 01:14:11.520
You've gone through two
or three board members.

01:14:11.520 --> 01:14:13.950
They totally forgot why they
invested in the first time.

01:14:13.950 --> 01:14:18.420
They're not professional
investors like VCs.

01:14:18.420 --> 01:14:22.810
And you inevitably end
with-- not inevitably.

01:14:22.810 --> 01:14:26.420
You very, very often
end with situations

01:14:26.420 --> 01:14:30.040
where there's a lawyer for
some strategic investor sitting

01:14:30.040 --> 01:14:33.080
there reading the fine print of
the legal agreement done eight

01:14:33.080 --> 01:14:36.030
years ago looking at
all the rights they have

01:14:36.030 --> 01:14:41.626
and really becoming a
nightmare to work with.

01:14:41.626 --> 01:14:44.780
I've been in situations where
the strategic investors,

01:14:44.780 --> 01:14:47.160
you're trying to go
public, strategic investor

01:14:47.160 --> 01:14:48.810
has a board seat.

01:14:48.810 --> 01:14:50.210
I'm not signing off on DS1.

01:14:50.210 --> 01:14:51.880
We don't want this
company to go public.

01:14:51.880 --> 01:14:53.460
People actually do that.

01:14:53.460 --> 01:14:58.560
Professional investors like
VCs would never ever do that.

01:14:58.560 --> 01:15:03.140
So I think having professional
investors on board first

01:15:03.140 --> 01:15:05.710
before you take on strategics
is a very good idea,

01:15:05.710 --> 01:15:09.390
because professional investors
help you get the terms and also

01:15:09.390 --> 01:15:13.750
relative ownership and all of
that right with strategics.

01:15:13.750 --> 01:15:16.370
And I've just seen
it so many times,

01:15:16.370 --> 01:15:19.460
that it may even be
great for a few years.

01:15:19.460 --> 01:15:21.550
But over the life of
a typical company,

01:15:21.550 --> 01:15:26.072
you very frequently run
into significant issues.

01:15:26.072 --> 01:15:27.530
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN:
The other thing

01:15:27.530 --> 01:15:29.920
that I've seen happen
again and again

01:15:29.920 --> 01:15:37.670
is where there have been large
numbers of early investors,

01:15:37.670 --> 01:15:40.870
whether they're friends and
family or loosely affiliated

01:15:40.870 --> 01:15:45.190
angels or what have
you, and someone

01:15:45.190 --> 01:15:50.020
has made the oversight of
making decisions unanimous.

01:15:50.020 --> 01:15:51.340
This is a nightmare.

01:15:51.340 --> 01:15:54.550
Because what ends up happening
is you might have, who knows,

01:15:54.550 --> 01:15:59.190
17 or 20 or God knows how many
individual parties who have

01:15:59.190 --> 01:16:03.000
to sign off on every
subsequent thing that happens.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:05.770
And I've seen this
happen many times.

01:16:05.770 --> 01:16:07.430
It it's a terrible mistake.

01:16:07.430 --> 01:16:12.230
It costs an incredible amount
of time to fix that and go back.

01:16:12.230 --> 01:16:14.410
And I've seen
individual investors

01:16:14.410 --> 01:16:18.710
who have put $10,000
into a company

01:16:18.710 --> 01:16:23.720
just tie up deals for days or
weeks or even scotch deals.

01:16:23.720 --> 01:16:26.740
So not just strategic,
not signing an S1,

01:16:26.740 --> 01:16:34.230
but individual very, very tiny
investors preventing a deal

01:16:34.230 --> 01:16:36.890
from happening.

01:16:36.890 --> 01:16:38.860
So if you do the friends
and family route--

01:16:38.860 --> 01:16:42.190
I would not advise you not to do
that-- just make sure that you

01:16:42.190 --> 01:16:43.970
have good counsel.

01:16:43.970 --> 01:16:47.080
You don't have the benefit
of a professional investor

01:16:47.080 --> 01:16:47.750
to advise you.

01:16:47.750 --> 01:16:52.620
Make sure you have good counsel
to structure that round so

01:16:52.620 --> 01:16:57.110
that you're not bound to
having every single person

01:16:57.110 --> 01:16:59.985
participating agree with
every future decision

01:16:59.985 --> 01:17:03.138
you have to make

01:17:03.138 --> 01:17:04.990
AMIR NASHAT: I'm going
to give a squishy--

01:17:04.990 --> 01:17:06.540
like an early
biomarker or squishy

01:17:06.540 --> 01:17:11.030
answer for how I kind
of have viewed people I

01:17:11.030 --> 01:17:12.380
have found difficult work with.

01:17:12.380 --> 01:17:14.920
Again, we're kind of in the
same boat most of entrepreneurs

01:17:14.920 --> 01:17:15.710
are in.

01:17:15.710 --> 01:17:16.442
We invest early.

01:17:16.442 --> 01:17:18.650
We bring other VCs on the
board and we get frustrated

01:17:18.650 --> 01:17:20.280
by our colleagues.

01:17:20.280 --> 01:17:22.960
So we're like, pulling out
our hair, too, sometimes.

01:17:22.960 --> 01:17:28.290
And so I've always found
that investors that actually

01:17:28.290 --> 01:17:30.040
ask a lot of
questions-- and it's

01:17:30.040 --> 01:17:31.840
very specific to
a particular deal.

01:17:31.840 --> 01:17:36.730
Someone who's a good listener
asks questions and is just

01:17:36.730 --> 01:17:39.110
listening and
questioning is usually

01:17:39.110 --> 01:17:40.580
probably a better investor.

01:17:40.580 --> 01:17:43.430
Whenever I've been in these
kind of nightmare situations,

01:17:43.430 --> 01:17:45.180
you later kind of
remember that, you know,

01:17:45.180 --> 01:17:46.930
they didn't really ask
a lot of questions.

01:17:46.930 --> 01:17:48.230
They just told me a lot stuff.

01:17:48.230 --> 01:17:51.380
They kept lecturing me
about my idea, my company.

01:17:51.380 --> 01:17:54.110
I think usually that's
like my first alarm bell

01:17:54.110 --> 01:17:56.030
whenever we're
involved in stuff.

01:17:56.030 --> 01:17:58.510
And it can go wrong
1,000 different ways.

01:17:58.510 --> 01:18:01.500
But if they're not asking
you interesting questions

01:18:01.500 --> 01:18:05.560
and listening, you're probably
in for a bruising relationship,

01:18:05.560 --> 01:18:06.566
in my opinion.

01:18:06.566 --> 01:18:07.940
And the sooner
you get-- and then

01:18:07.940 --> 01:18:10.680
reference checks, whoever
said that earlier-- Axel had

01:18:10.680 --> 01:18:13.570
say reference the
hell out of investors.

01:18:13.570 --> 01:18:15.825
We do.

01:18:15.825 --> 01:18:19.680
PROFESSOR: We're coming
up close to break time.

01:18:19.680 --> 01:18:21.390
Maybe one last
question and then I'll

01:18:21.390 --> 01:18:23.777
ask the panel if you
have any last comments.

01:18:23.777 --> 01:18:25.360
Don't feel you have
to, but if there's

01:18:25.360 --> 01:18:27.010
something that's pressing.

01:18:27.010 --> 01:18:28.412
Was there a question over there?

01:18:28.412 --> 01:18:29.328
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:18:43.440 --> 01:18:45.511
Do you know they
are going to have

01:18:45.511 --> 01:18:47.750
to be part of the
gang that's employed,

01:18:47.750 --> 01:18:50.402
would you go talk
to them straightaway

01:18:50.402 --> 01:18:52.250
if they were very [INAUDIBLE].

01:19:05.380 --> 01:19:08.970
AMIR NASHAT: I'll give
you a general answer.

01:19:08.970 --> 01:19:11.360
I think you should get
rid of your biggest

01:19:11.360 --> 01:19:15.210
risk with the least amount
of money as fast as possible.

01:19:15.210 --> 01:19:19.710
And the way you described the
situation maybe your friend

01:19:19.710 --> 01:19:22.290
has-- it's like, my friend
has a rash, at the doctor--

01:19:22.290 --> 01:19:25.199
[LAUGHTER]

01:19:25.699 --> 01:19:30.160
I guess is basically
like, if there's

01:19:30.160 --> 01:19:32.799
a point at which you are stuck,
then you should get unstuck.

01:19:32.799 --> 01:19:33.840
I'll give you an example.

01:19:33.840 --> 01:19:36.610
Sun Catalytics is a
really good example.

01:19:36.610 --> 01:19:38.332
If I'd gone to my
partners-- we were

01:19:38.332 --> 01:19:39.540
developing this energy stuff.

01:19:39.540 --> 01:19:42.120
And one of the big
markets was India

01:19:42.120 --> 01:19:43.720
initially for the company.

01:19:43.720 --> 01:19:45.784
If I'd gone to my
partners and said,

01:19:45.784 --> 01:19:47.450
hey, we need to put
in a bunch of money.

01:19:47.450 --> 01:19:48.060
It's going to be great.

01:19:48.060 --> 01:19:49.800
We're going to go commercialize
in India and all this.

01:19:49.800 --> 01:19:50.795
Or any other VC people.

01:19:50.795 --> 01:19:51.545
They'd say, India?

01:19:51.545 --> 01:19:53.010
What are you going to do there?

01:19:53.010 --> 01:19:55.230
So very, very early in
the life of the company,

01:19:55.230 --> 01:19:58.200
I realized we needed to have
that fixed, because it's

01:19:58.200 --> 01:20:00.390
a major risk that one
of our largest markets

01:20:00.390 --> 01:20:01.302
was one nobody new.

01:20:01.302 --> 01:20:02.510
So we went and we did a deal.

01:20:02.510 --> 01:20:04.480
We got an investment
and partnership dollars

01:20:04.480 --> 01:20:06.820
from the Totten Group.

01:20:06.820 --> 01:20:09.470
I've never heard that
question in four or five

01:20:09.470 --> 01:20:10.640
years about the company.

01:20:10.640 --> 01:20:12.320
We can say anything about India.

01:20:12.320 --> 01:20:14.362
Yeah, we're going to go
sell spaceships in India.

01:20:14.362 --> 01:20:16.111
They're like, oh yeah,
you're with Totten?

01:20:16.111 --> 01:20:16.940
No problem.

01:20:16.940 --> 01:20:19.496
And we just basically got
rid of the biggest risk

01:20:19.496 --> 01:20:20.995
which was this
perception that there

01:20:20.995 --> 01:20:23.540
was no market by solving it.

01:20:23.540 --> 01:20:27.600
Now could we have gotten
better terms later or whatever?

01:20:27.600 --> 01:20:30.650
Maybe, but I got rid
of it at the earliest

01:20:30.650 --> 01:20:32.560
point in the context of deal.

01:20:32.560 --> 01:20:35.772
And so if you're really going
to be stuck with these guys,

01:20:35.772 --> 01:20:37.480
I think you're going
to worry about that,

01:20:37.480 --> 01:20:40.021
that you don't get rid of your
big-- whatever your risks are.

01:20:40.021 --> 01:20:42.580
I always kind of list them and
I say the biggest one first.

01:20:45.562 --> 01:20:47.880
JULIANNE ZIMMERMAN:
I absolutely agree.

01:20:47.880 --> 01:20:51.780
The other thing that I think you
want to be really careful about

01:20:51.780 --> 01:20:58.240
is if there's honest to God
only one major player you need

01:20:58.240 --> 01:21:00.530
to cooperate with
you and whatever

01:21:00.530 --> 01:21:03.020
that means-- first
of all, you want

01:21:03.020 --> 01:21:05.520
to make sure you're not
going down a cul-de-sac.

01:21:05.520 --> 01:21:07.672
Not only do you want
to retire the risk,

01:21:07.672 --> 01:21:09.380
but you want to make
sure that you're not

01:21:09.380 --> 01:21:12.320
aiming for something
that's not going to exist

01:21:12.320 --> 01:21:14.310
when you're ready to get there.

01:21:14.310 --> 01:21:18.190
So you really want to understand
what's in it for them,

01:21:18.190 --> 01:21:23.370
not just now, but when
you're ready in whatever,

01:21:23.370 --> 01:21:25.290
a year or five years.

01:21:25.290 --> 01:21:30.166
Are you aiming for a place
where they will no longer be?

01:21:30.166 --> 01:21:31.540
Because what you
don't want to do

01:21:31.540 --> 01:21:38.430
is spend that next chunk of your
life going into a blind alley.

01:21:38.430 --> 01:21:40.460
And I wasn't here last night.

01:21:40.460 --> 01:21:41.575
I miss Bob's talk.

01:21:41.575 --> 01:21:42.654
But I've seen it before.

01:21:42.654 --> 01:21:44.570
And if I remember
correctly, one of the things

01:21:44.570 --> 01:21:46.880
that he likes to say
is, go talk to people

01:21:46.880 --> 01:21:48.200
and don't try to sell them.

01:21:48.200 --> 01:21:50.380
Just have a hypothetical
conversation.

01:21:50.380 --> 01:21:54.810
If I had this, would
that interest you?

01:21:54.810 --> 01:21:58.240
I understand your interests
like this, do I have that right?

01:21:58.240 --> 01:22:02.840
Do I understand what
you really want?

01:22:02.840 --> 01:22:05.460
You can have those
conversations without having

01:22:05.460 --> 01:22:08.760
to make big disclosures,
without having to formalize

01:22:08.760 --> 01:22:11.630
any kind of relationship.

01:22:11.630 --> 01:22:15.950
And just like you want your
investors to ask questions,

01:22:15.950 --> 01:22:17.750
you want to be asking
a lot of questions

01:22:17.750 --> 01:22:20.440
along the way of
any party you're

01:22:20.440 --> 01:22:22.600
going to be working with.

01:22:22.600 --> 01:22:24.530
And if it's really
true that you are

01:22:24.530 --> 01:22:27.250
going to be dependent
on this one entity,

01:22:27.250 --> 01:22:30.140
then you really
need to understand

01:22:30.140 --> 01:22:34.260
how vital it is to
them that they're

01:22:34.260 --> 01:22:38.230
going to get to have access
to whatever you're developing.

01:22:38.230 --> 01:22:42.950
And you need to stay very
close to that vital interest

01:22:42.950 --> 01:22:48.870
because even if you sign a deal
with them today, as Axel said,

01:22:48.870 --> 01:22:50.510
people change roles.

01:22:50.510 --> 01:22:53.180
They go on and work
for another company.

01:22:53.180 --> 01:22:56.340
You lose a champion,
and if you don't already

01:22:56.340 --> 01:23:00.370
have a deeper connection
with that organization,

01:23:00.370 --> 01:23:02.120
you could be talking
to a lawyer, which

01:23:02.120 --> 01:23:04.680
is not a really great feeling.

01:23:04.680 --> 01:23:07.650
So yeah, you definitely want
to prioritize your risks.

01:23:07.650 --> 01:23:08.650
You want to retire them.

01:23:08.650 --> 01:23:12.630
You also really want to
understand if you're really

01:23:12.630 --> 01:23:15.550
pinning your prospects
on this one company,

01:23:15.550 --> 01:23:17.750
you better make sure
that they're going

01:23:17.750 --> 01:23:20.205
to be there when you get there.

01:23:20.205 --> 01:23:27.260
AXEL BICHARA: So I would
get the deal done early,

01:23:27.260 --> 01:23:31.570
at least get started early,
but get people experienced

01:23:31.570 --> 01:23:33.970
with deal making on
board, whether it's

01:23:33.970 --> 01:23:37.350
an investor, advisory,
friend of the company.

01:23:37.350 --> 01:23:39.750
Some of these big
strategic deals,

01:23:39.750 --> 01:23:42.250
they may take more than
a year to get done.

01:23:42.250 --> 01:23:47.520
And the way to think about them
is really like a chess game.

01:23:47.520 --> 01:23:49.300
You need to think
a bunch of moves

01:23:49.300 --> 01:23:52.330
ahead to really
achieve your objective.

01:23:52.330 --> 01:23:59.380
And I'm a big believer
in skilled negotiation

01:23:59.380 --> 01:24:01.700
actually creating
value fundamentally

01:24:01.700 --> 01:24:04.190
because you find win-wins,
alignment of interests,

01:24:04.190 --> 01:24:07.130
and you may only
discover that after five

01:24:07.130 --> 01:24:09.710
or six moves in the chess game.

01:24:09.710 --> 01:24:16.700
And people who have done that
many times in their lives,

01:24:16.700 --> 01:24:19.504
just from experience, turns out
they can add a lot of value.

01:24:19.504 --> 01:24:20.920
So that maybe
another perspective.

